{"title_page": "Affiliate (commerce)", "text_new": "{{notability|date=November 2017}}\n{{dictionary}}\nThe term affiliate is used to describe the relationship between two entities wherein one owns less than a majority stake in the other's stock. Affiliations can also describe a type of relationship in which at least two different companies are subsidiaries of a larger parent company.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chen |first1=James |title=Affiliate - Business Essentials |url=https://www.investopedia.com/terms/a/affiliate.asp |website=Investopedia |publisher=Dotdash |accessdate=14 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Corporate structure ==\nA [[corporation]] may be referred to as an \"affiliate\" of another when it is related to it but not strictly controlled by it, as with a [[subsidiary]] relationship, or when it is desired to avoid the appearance of control. This is sometimes seen with companies that need to avoid restrictive laws (or negative public opinion) on foreign ownership.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Affiliate marketing]]\n* [[Associate company]]\n* [[Franchising]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Affiliate marketing]]\n\n[https://Oprice.in Popular Affiliate]\n\n[https://oprice.in/product/high-performance-wi-fi-router-mi-r4cm-300-mbps/ Wifi Router]\n", "text_old": "{{notability|date=November 2017}}\n{{dictionary}}\nThe term affiliate is used to describe the relationship between two entities wherein one owns less than a majority stake in the other's stock. Affiliations can also describe a type of relationship in which at least two different companies are subsidiaries of a larger parent company.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chen |first1=James |title=Affiliate - Business Essentials |url=https://www.investopedia.com/terms/a/affiliate.asp |website=Investopedia |publisher=Dotdash |accessdate=14 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Corporate structure ==\nA [[corporation]] may be referred to as an \"affiliate\" of another when it is related to it but not strictly controlled by it, as with a [[subsidiary]] relationship, or when it is desired to avoid the appearance of control. This is sometimes seen with companies that need to avoid restrictive laws (or negative public opinion) on foreign ownership.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Affiliate marketing]]\n* [[Associate company]]\n* [[Franchising]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Affiliate marketing]]\n", "name_user": "103.69.25.123", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eReferences)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Affiliate_(commerce)"}
{"title_page": "Riki", "text_new": "{{for|the given name|Riki (given name)}}\n{{Spanish name|S\u00e1nchez-Rico|Soto}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Riki\n| image = Riki - Deporitvo La Coruna.jpg\n| caption = Riki playing with [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo]] in 2012\n| fullname = Iv\u00e1n S\u00e1nchez-Rico Soto\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1980|8|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Aranjuez]], Spain\n| height = {{convert|1.87|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| position = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = 1986\u20131995 | youthclubs1 = Loyola\n| youthyears2 = 1995\u20131999 | youthclubs2 = Ancora Aranjuez\n| years1 = 1999\u20132000 | clubs1 = [[Real Aranjuez CF|Aranjuez]] | caps1 = | goals1 =\n| years2 = 2000\u20132002 | clubs2 = [[Real Madrid C]] | caps2 = | goals2 = \n| years3 = 2002\u20132004 | clubs3 = [[Real Madrid Castilla|Real Madrid B]] | caps3 = 51 | goals3 = 20\n| years4 = 2004\u20132006 | clubs4 = [[Getafe CF|Getafe]] | caps4 = 61 | goals4 = 10\n| years5 = 2006\u20132013 | clubs5 = [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a]] | caps5 = 204 | goals5 = 52\n| years6 = 2013\u20132015 | clubs6 = [[Granada CF|Granada]] | caps6 = 36 | goals6 = 2\n| years7 = 2015\u20132016 | clubs7 = [[CD Guadalajara (Spain)|Guadalajara]] | caps7 = 11 | goals7 = 4\n| totalcaps = 363 | totalgoals = 88 \n| club-update =\n}}\n'''Iv\u00e1n S\u00e1nchez-Rico Soto''' (born 11 August 1980), known as '''Riki''', is a Spanish former [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]].\n\nHe spent most of his professional career with [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo]], appearing in 226 competitive games and scoring 58 goals.\n\n==Club career==\n===Early career===\nRiki was born in [[Aranjuez]], [[Community of Madrid]]. After spending his youth career in amateur clubs in the area he played with both [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]]'s reserve sides, [[Real Madrid C|C]] and [[Real Madrid Castilla|B]]. In July 2004, after having signed an extension with the ''Merengues'' the previous year,<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=115769.html Madrid tie up striking starlets]; UEFA, 3 October 2003</ref> he was released and moved to another [[Madrid|capital]] team, [[Getafe CF]], making his [[La Liga]] debut on 12 September 2004 in a 1\u20132 home defeat to [[RCD Mallorca]];<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundodeporte/2004/09/12/liga/1095021173.html|title=El Mallorca amarga el debut del Getafe|trans-title=Mallorca bitter Getafe's debut|newspaper=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|language=es|date=12 September 2004|accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref> on 13 March 2005 he scored against his former employer in a 2\u20131 home victory<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=287685.html Riki rocks Madrid title dreams]; UEFA, 14 March 2005</ref> and, in [[2005\u201306 La Liga|his second season]], netted eight league goals.\n\n===Deportivo===\nIn late June 2006, Riki moved to [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a]] on a five-year contract.<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=431672.html Riki ripe for Deportivo]; UEFA, 22 June 2006</ref> During [[2006\u201307 La Liga|his first year]] he was an undisputed starter and, in [[2007\u201308 La Liga|the following campaign]], he featured less prominently, but scored two more goals (five).\n\nIn the first game of the [[2008\u201309 La Liga|2008\u201309 season]], against Real Madrid, Riki was stretchered off the pitch with a [[hamstring]] injury, ironically after having [[Substitute (association football)|subbed in]] himself.<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/252961?cc=5739 Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a 2\u20131 Real Madrid]; [[ESPN FC|ESPN Soccernet]], 31 August 2008</ref> He was out of action for two weeks,<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=746158.html Depor striker Riki ruled out for weeks]; UEFA, 3 September 2008</ref> subsequently netting on 2 November 2008 in a 3\u20130 away defeat of [[Real Betis]].<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/252767?cc=5739 Real Betis 0\u20133 Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a]; ESPN Soccernet, 2 November 2008</ref>\n\nRiki again suffered physical problems in [[2009\u201310 La Liga|the following season]], but made the most of his 1,492 minutes as he scored eight goals, notably netting in the first round, a 2\u20133 loss at Real Madrid,<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/275652?cc=5739 Real Madrid 3\u20132 Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a]; ESPN Soccernet, 29 August 2009</ref> and in both matches against [[Xerez CD]] (3\u20130 away, 2\u20131 at home);<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/275908?cc=5739 Xerez continue to struggle]; ESPN Soccernet, 23 September 2009</ref><ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/275702?cc=5739 Early goals seal Depor victory]; ESPN Soccernet, 20 February 2010</ref> the [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicians]] eventually finished in tenth position.\n\nAfter his team's relegation in [[2010\u201311 La Liga|2011]], Riki netted 14 times as they [[2011\u201312 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|bounced back]] as champions of the second division, including early strikes in home and away victories over [[RC Celta de Vigo]] in the [[Galician derby]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2011/11/13/futbol/2adivision/1321218402.html|title=En Galicia manda el D\u00e9por|trans-title=D\u00e9por rule in Galicia|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|language=es|date=13 November 2011|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lavozdegalicia.es/noticia/deportes/2012/04/15/deportivo-vence-celta-derbi-gallego-recuerdo/00031334491134401833734.htm|title=El Deportivo vence al Celta en un derbi gallego para el recuerdo|trans-title=Deportivo defeat Celta in a Galician derby to remember|newspaper=[[La Voz de Galicia]]|language=es|date=16 April 2012|accessdate=25 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Later years===\nWhen Deportivo were [[2012\u201313 La Liga|immediately relegated]], Riki ended his seven-year tenure to remain in the top flight at [[Granada CF]] for the next three seasons.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2013/06/22/futbol/equipos/granada/1371910326.html|title=Riki jugar\u00e1 en el Granada las tres pr\u00f3ximas temporadas|trans-title=Riki will play the next three seasons at Granada|newspaper=Marca|language=es|date=22 June 2013|accessdate=25 January 2017}}</ref> He did not score for the [[Andalusia]]ns until 14 December 2013 in a 2\u20130 win at [[Rayo Vallecano]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/r-vallecano-vs-granada/304404|title=Rayo Vallecano 0\u20132 Granada|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|date=14 December 2013|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref> and added only one more goal in a 3\u20133 draw on his return to Getafe.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.es/deportes/futbol/20140315/abci-getafe-granada-cronica-201403150028.html|title=Reparto de puntos entre Getafe y Granada en un partido loco|trans-title=Getafe and Granada share the points in a crazy match|newspaper=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]|language=es|date=15 March 2014|accessdate=25 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 August 2015, 35-year-old Riki dropped down two levels to sign a two-year deal at [[CD Guadalajara (Spain)|CD Guadalajara]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deportivoguadalajara.es/riki-un-refuerzo-de-primera-para-el-c-d-guadalajara/|title=Riki, un refuerzo de Primera para el C.D. Guadalajara|trans-title=Riki, ''Primera'' addition for C.D. Guadalajara|publisher=CD Guadalajara|language=es|date=31 August 2015|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref> He left at the end of [[2015\u201316 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|his debut campaign]], however, having been relegated from [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cadenaser.com/emisora/2016/05/19/ser_guadalajara/1463662644_391258.html|title=El Deportivo Guadalajara pone punto y final a la peor temporada de los \u00faltimos 34 a\u00f1os|trans-title=Deportivo Guadalajara bid farewell to worst season of last 34 years|publisher=[[Cadena SER]]|language=es|date=19 May 2016|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n'''Deportivo'''\n*[[UEFA Intertoto Cup]]: [[2008 UEFA Intertoto Cup|2008]]\n*[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]]: [[2011\u201312 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2011\u201312]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|1154}}\n*{{Futbolme profile|20159}}\n*{{Soccerway|ivan-sanchez-rico-soto/3081}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Riki}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Aranjuez]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Madrilenian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Real Madrid C footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Madrid Castilla footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Madrid CF players]]\n[[Category:Getafe CF footballers]]\n[[Category:Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a players]]\n[[Category:Granada CF footballers]]\n[[Category:CD Guadalajara (Spain) footballers]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the given name|Riki (given name)}}\n{{Spanish name|S\u00e1nchez-Rico|Soto}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Riki\n| image = Riki - Deporitvo La Coruna.jpg\n| caption = Riki playing with [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo]] in 2012\n| fullname = Iv\u00e1n S\u00e1nchez-Rico Soto\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1980|8|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Aranjuez]], Spain\n| height = {{convert|1.87|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| position = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = 1986\u20131995 | youthclubs1 = Loyola\n| youthyears2 = 1995\u20131999 | youthclubs2 = Ancora Aranjuez\n| years1 = 1999\u20132000 | clubs1 = [[Real Aranjuez CF|Aranjuez]] | caps1 = | goals1 =\n| years2 = 2000\u20132002 | clubs2 = [[Real Madrid C]] | caps2 = | goals2 = \n| years3 = 2002\u20132004 | clubs3 = [[Real Madrid Castilla|Real Madrid B]] | caps3 = 51 | goals3 = 20\n| years4 = 2004\u20132006 | clubs4 = [[Getafe CF|Getafe]] | caps4 = 61 | goals4 = 10\n| years5 = 2006\u20132013 | clubs5 = [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a]] | caps5 = 204 | goals5 = 52\n| years6 = 2013\u20132015 | clubs6 = [[Granada CF|Granada]] | caps6 = 36 | goals6 = 2\n| years7 = 2015\u20132016 | clubs7 = [[CD Guadalajara (Spain)|Guadalajara]] | caps7 = 11 | goals7 = 4\n| totalcaps = 363 | totalgoals = 88 \n| club-update =\n}}\n'''Iv\u00e1n S\u00e1nchez-Rico Soto''' (born 11 August 1980), known as '''Riki''', is a Spanish former [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]].\n\nHe spent most of his professional career with [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo]], appearing in 226 competitive games and scoring 58 goals.\n\n==Club career==\n===Early career===\nRiki was born in [[Aranjuez]], [[Community of Madrid]]. After spending his youth career in amateur clubs in the area he played with both [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]]'s reserve sides, [[Real Madrid C|C]] and [[Real Madrid Castilla|B]]. In July 2004, after having signed an extension with the ''Merengues'' the previous year,<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=115769.html Madrid tie up striking starlets]; UEFA, 3 October 2003</ref> he was released and moved to another [[Madrid|capital]] team, [[Getafe CF]], making his [[La Liga]] debut on 12 September 2004 in a 1\u20132 home defeat to [[RCD Mallorca]];<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundodeporte/2004/09/12/liga/1095021173.html|title=El Mallorca amarga el debut del Getafe|trans-title=Mallorca bitter Getafe's debut|newspaper=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|language=es|date=12 September 2004|accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref> on 13 March 2005 he scored against his former employer in a 2\u20131 home victory<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=287685.html Riki rocks Madrid title dreams]; UEFA, 14 March 2005</ref> and, in [[2005\u201306 La Liga|his second season]], netted eight league goals.\n\n===Deportivo===\nIn late June 2006, Riki moved to [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a]] on a five-year contract.<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=431672.html Riki ripe for Deportivo]; UEFA, 22 June 2006</ref> During [[2006\u201307 La Liga|his first year]] he was an undisputed starter and, in [[2007\u201308 La Liga|the following campaign]], he featured less prominently, but scored two more goals (five).\n\nIn the first game of the [[2008\u201309 La Liga|2008\u201309 season]], against Real Madrid, Riki was stretchered off the pitch with a [[hamstring]] injury, ironically after having [[Substitute (association football)|subbed in]] himself.<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/252961?cc=5739 Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a 2\u20131 Real Madrid]; [[ESPN FC|ESPN Soccernet]], 31 August 2008</ref> He was out of action for two weeks,<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=746158.html Depor striker Riki ruled out for weeks]; UEFA, 3 September 2008</ref> subsequently netting on 2 November 2008 in a 3\u20130 away defeat of [[Real Betis]].<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/252767?cc=5739 Real Betis 0\u20133 Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a]; ESPN Soccernet, 2 November 2008</ref>\n\nRiki again suffered physical problems in [[2009\u201310 La Liga|the following season]], but made the most of his 1,492 minutes as he scored eight goals, notably netting in the opener, a 2\u20133 loss at Real Madrid,<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/275652?cc=5739 Real Madrid 3\u20132 Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a]; ESPN Soccernet, 29 August 2009</ref> and in both matches against [[Xerez CD]] (3\u20130 away, 2\u20131 at home);<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/275908?cc=5739 Xerez continue to struggle]; ESPN Soccernet, 23 September 2009</ref><ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/275702?cc=5739 Early goals seal Depor victory]; ESPN Soccernet, 20 February 2010</ref> the [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicians]] eventually finished in tenth position.\n\nAfter his team's relegation in [[2010\u201311 La Liga|2011]], Riki netted 14 times as they [[2011\u201312 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|bounced back]] as champions of the second division, including early strikes in home and away victories over [[RC Celta de Vigo]] in the [[Galician derby]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2011/11/13/futbol/2adivision/1321218402.html|title=En Galicia manda el D\u00e9por|trans-title=D\u00e9por rule in Galicia|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|language=es|date=13 November 2011|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lavozdegalicia.es/noticia/deportes/2012/04/15/deportivo-vence-celta-derbi-gallego-recuerdo/00031334491134401833734.htm|title=El Deportivo vence al Celta en un derbi gallego para el recuerdo|trans-title=Deportivo defeat Celta in a Galician derby to remember|newspaper=[[La Voz de Galicia]]|language=es|date=16 April 2012|accessdate=25 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Later years===\nWhen Deportivo were [[2012\u201313 La Liga|immediately relegated]], Riki ended his seven-year tenure to remain in the top flight at [[Granada CF]] for the next three seasons.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2013/06/22/futbol/equipos/granada/1371910326.html|title=Riki jugar\u00e1 en el Granada las tres pr\u00f3ximas temporadas|trans-title=Riki will play the next three seasons at Granada|newspaper=Marca|language=es|date=22 June 2013|accessdate=25 January 2017}}</ref> He did not score for the [[Andalusia]]ns until 14 December 2013 in a 2\u20130 win at [[Rayo Vallecano]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/r-vallecano-vs-granada/304404|title=Rayo Vallecano 0\u20132 Granada|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|date=14 December 2013|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref> and added only one more goal in a 3\u20133 draw on his return to Getafe.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.es/deportes/futbol/20140315/abci-getafe-granada-cronica-201403150028.html|title=Reparto de puntos entre Getafe y Granada en un partido loco|trans-title=Getafe and Granada share the points in a crazy match|newspaper=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]|language=es|date=15 March 2014|accessdate=25 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 August 2015, 35-year-old Riki dropped down two levels to sign a two-year deal at [[CD Guadalajara (Spain)|CD Guadalajara]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deportivoguadalajara.es/riki-un-refuerzo-de-primera-para-el-c-d-guadalajara/|title=Riki, un refuerzo de Primera para el C.D. Guadalajara|trans-title=Riki, ''Primera'' addition for C.D. Guadalajara|publisher=CD Guadalajara|language=es|date=31 August 2015|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref> He left at the end of [[2015\u201316 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|his debut campaign]], however, having been relegated from [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cadenaser.com/emisora/2016/05/19/ser_guadalajara/1463662644_391258.html|title=El Deportivo Guadalajara pone punto y final a la peor temporada de los \u00faltimos 34 a\u00f1os|trans-title=Deportivo Guadalajara bid farewell to worst season of last 34 years|publisher=[[Cadena SER]]|language=es|date=19 May 2016|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n'''Deportivo'''\n*[[UEFA Intertoto Cup]]: [[2008 UEFA Intertoto Cup|2008]]\n*[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]]: [[2011\u201312 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2011\u201312]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|1154}}\n*{{Futbolme profile|20159}}\n*{{Soccerway|ivan-sanchez-rico-soto/3081}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Riki}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Aranjuez]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Madrilenian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Real Madrid C footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Madrid Castilla footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Madrid CF players]]\n[[Category:Getafe CF footballers]]\n[[Category:Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a players]]\n[[Category:Granada CF footballers]]\n[[Category:CD Guadalajara (Spain) footballers]]\n", "name_user": "Quite A Character", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDeportivo:Language.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riki"}
{"title_page": "Dustin Hoffman filmography", "text_new": "[[File:Dustin Hoffman Cannes.jpg|alt=Dustin Hoffman at Cannes|thumb|Dustin Hoffman at Cannes]]\nAmerican actor [[Dustin Hoffman]] began his career by appearing in an episode of ''[[Naked City (TV series)|Naked City]]'' in 1961. His first theatrical performance was 1961's ''A Cook for Mr. General'' as Ridzinski. Following several guest appearances on television, he starred in the 1966 play ''[[Eh? (play)|Eh?]]''; his performance garnered him both a [[Theatre World Award]] and [[Drama Desk Award]].<ref name=\"Playbill\">{{cite web|title=Dustin Hoffman|url=http://www.playbill.com/person/dustin-hoffman-vault-0000015166|website=[[Playbill]]|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> Hoffman made his film debut in 1967 when he appeared in the comedy ''[[The Tiger Makes Out]]''. In the same year, his breakthrough role as Benjamin \"Ben\" Braddock, the title character in [[Mike Nichols]]' comedy-drama ''[[The Graduate]]'', led to Hoffman achieving star status and his first [[Academy Award]] nomination.<ref name=\"Biography.com\">{{cite web|author=Biography.com Editors|title=Dustin Hoffman Biography|url=http://www.biography.com/people/dustin-hoffman-9341124#acting-career|website=[[Biography.com]]|publisher=[[A&E Television Networks]]|accessdate=May 5, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424235902/http://www.biography.com/people/dustin-hoffman-9341124#acting-career|archive-date=April 24, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> He then acted in the play ''Jimmy Shine'' as the eponymous character and the comedy film ''[[Madigan's Millions]]'' (both 1968). In 1969, he starred alongside [[Jon Voight]] in the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]] winner ''[[Midnight Cowboy]]'', which Hoffman was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Actor]] a second time.<ref name=\"Biography.com\"/>\n\nThe 1970s saw Hoffman star in several critically acclaimed and commercially successful films, including the Western ''[[Little Big Man (film)|Little Big Man]]'' (1970), psychological thriller ''[[Straw Dogs (1971 film)|Straw Dogs]]'' (1971), prison film ''[[Papillon (1973 film)|Papillon]]'' (1973) alongside [[Steve McQueen]], ''[[Lenny (film)|Lenny]]'' (1974) about the controversial comedian [[Lenny Bruce]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Canby|first1=Vincent|title='Lenny,' With Dustin Hoffman, Is One --Fourth Brilliant|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9404E4D9133BE63BBC4952DFB767838F669EDE|website=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=May 5, 2016|date=November 11, 1974}}</ref> and the political thriller ''[[All the President's Men (film)|All the President's Men]]'' (1976) as journalist [[Carl Bernstein]] investigating the [[Watergate scandal]] alongside [[Bob Woodward]] (played by Robert Redford).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tunzelmann|first1=Alex von|title=All the President's Men: Hoffman and Redford fight the powers that be|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/oct/10/all-the-presidents-men-watergate-conspiracy-richard-nixon-woodward-bernstein-redford-hoffman|website=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=May 5, 2016|date=October 10, 2014}}</ref> After starring in the suspense-thriller ''[[Marathon Man (film)|Marathon Man]]'' (1976) and the crime drama ''[[Straight Time]]'' (1978), Hoffman starred in the 1979 drama ''[[Kramer vs. Kramer]]'', which he won the Academy Award for Best Actor for the first time for his performance as Ted Kramer.<ref name=\"Biography.com\"/>\n\nAfter a three-year acting hiatus, he starred in the comedy ''[[Tootsie]]'' in 1982 as a struggling actor who pretends to be a woman in order to get an acting role. He returned to stage acting with a 1984 performance as [[Willy Loman]] in ''[[Death of a Salesman]]'' \u2013 Hoffman reprised the role a year later in a television film.<ref name=\"Biography.com\"/> 1987 saw the release of originally ill-received comedy ''[[Ishtar (film)|Ishtar]]'', in which he starred with [[Warren Beatty]]; its critical support has since grown.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brody|first1=Richard|title=To Wish Upon Ishtar|url=http://www.newyorker.com/culture/richard-brody/to-wish-upon-ishtar|website=[[The New Yorker]]|accessdate=May 5, 2016|date=August 9, 2010}}</ref> He won his second Academy Award for Best Actor for his portrayal of the [[autistic]] savant Ray Babbitt in the 1988 film ''[[Rain Man]]'', co-starring [[Tom Cruise]].<ref name=\"Biography.com\"/>  In 1989, he was nominated for a [[Tony Award]] and a Drama Desk Award for playing [[Shylock]] in a stage performance of ''[[The Merchant of Venice]]''.<ref name=\"Playbill\"/> In the 1990s, he made appearances in such film as [[Warren Beatty]]'s action comedy adaptation ''[[Dick Tracy (1990 film)|Dick Tracy]]'' (1990), [[Steven Spielberg]]'s ''[[Hook (film)|Hook]]'' (1991) as [[Captain Hook]], guest starred in the 1991 \"[[Lisa's Substitute]]\" episode of ''[[The Simpsons]]'', medical disaster ''[[Outbreak (film)|Outbreak]]'' (1995), legal crime drama ''[[Sleepers (film)|Sleepers]]'' (1996), thriller ''[[Mad City (film)|Mad City]]'' (1997), and the satirical black comedy ''[[Wag the Dog]]'' (1997) alongside [[Robert De Niro]].\n\nIn the 2000s, he played theatrical producer [[Charles Frohman]] in ''[[Finding Neverland (film)|Finding Neverland]]'', co-starred in the comedy ''[[Meet the Fockers]]'' (both 2004) as Bernie Focker, the fantasy thriller ''[[Perfume: The Story of a Murderer (film)|Perfume: The Story of a Murderer]]'' (2006), and played the title character in the family comedy ''[[Mr. Magorium's Wonder Emporium]]'' (2007). Hoffman has acted in the ''[[Kung Fu Panda (franchise)|Kung Fu Panda]]'' franchise since 2008 and reprised his role as Focker in ''[[Little Fockers]]'' (2010). He starred in the [[HBO]] drama series ''[[Luck (TV series)|Luck]]'', which was cancelled after one season due to animal safety concerns, and made his directorial debut in 2012 with ''[[Quartet (2012 film)|Quartet]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=French|first1=Phillip|title=Quartet \u2013 review|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/jan/06/quartet-review-film-dustin-hoffman|website=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=May 5, 2016|date=January 6, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Film==\n[[File:Dustin Hoffman - Little Big Man.jpg|thumb|Hoffman in 1968]]\n[[File:Hoffman-Midler - 1977.jpg|thumb|With [[Bette Midler]] on Bette Midler TV Special (1977)]]\n[[File:Dustin Hoffman - Salesman.jpg|thumb|in ''Death of a Salesman'' (1985)]]\n[[File:Dustin Hoffman Quartet avp 2013.jpg|thumb|Hoffman in Paris at the French premiere of  ''[[Quartet (2012 film)|Quartet]]'', March 2013]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"margin-right: 0;\"\n|+ Film credits of Dustin Hoffman\n|-\n!scope=\"col\" width=20% | Title\n!scope=\"col\" width=1% | Year\n!scope=\"col\" width=15% | Role\n!scope=\"col\" width=15% | Director(s)\n!scope=\"col\" width=10% class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n!scope=\"col\" width=2% class=\"unsortable\" | {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Tiger Makes Out]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1967\n| Hap\n| [[Arthur Hiller]]\n| \n|style=\"text-align: center;\"|<ref name=\"AFI\">{{cite web|title=Dustin Hoffman filmography (as of award year)|url=http://www.afi.com/laa/laa99f.aspx|website=[[American Film Institute]]|accessdate=22 April 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[The Graduate]]''\n| Benjamin \"Ben\" Braddock\n| [[Mike Nichols]]\n|  \n|style=\"text-align: center;\"|<ref name=\"AFI\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Madigan's Millions]]''\n| 1968\n| Jason Fister\n| [[Stanley Prager]]\n| \n|style=\"text-align: center;\"|<ref name=\"AFI\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Midnight Cowboy]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1969\n| Enrico Salvatore \"Ratso\" Rizzo\n| [[John Schlesinger]]\n|        \n|style=\"text-align: center;\"|<ref name=\"AFI\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[John and Mary (film)|John and Mary]]''\n| John\n| [[Peter Yates]]\n|             \n|style=\"text-align: center;\"|<ref name=\"AFI\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Little Big Man (film)|Little Big Man]]''\n| 1970\n| Jack Crabb\n| [