*[[Aboriginal rock]]\n*[[Vibe Australia]]\n*[[List of Indigenous Australian performing artists]]\n* [[Buried Country]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Indigenous Australian musical groups| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of Australians in music|Indigenous]]\n[[Category:Indigenous Australian musicians| ]]\n[[Category:Indigenous Australia-related lists|Musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Uanfala", "label": "safe", "comment": "DisambiguateYugultoYugul (band)usingpopups", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Indigenous_Australian_musicians"}
{"title_page": "Coronado Islands", "text_new": "{{Other places|Coronado (disambiguation){{!}}Coronado}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2008}}\n[[File:Coronado Islands Map.jpg|440x440px|A map of the four Coronado Islands.|thumb]]\n[[File:800px-Islas Coronado.cc.jpg|thumb|300px|right|<center>The Coronado Islands, viewed from Tijuana beach</center>]]\n[[File:Border Patrol Vehicle near U.S. Mexico Border.jpg|thumb|At the US-Mexico border. The visible islands are Islas Coronado]] \nThe '''Coronado Islands''' (''Islas Coronado'' or ''Islas Coronados''; {{lang-en|Islands of the Coronation(s)}}) are a group of four [[island]]s off the northwest coast of the [[Mexico|Mexican]] [[States of Mexico|state]] of [[Baja California]]. Battered by the wind and waves, they are largely barren and uninhabited except for a small military detachment and a few lighthouse keepers. The islands lie between 15 and 19 miles south of the entrance to [[San Diego]] bay, but only 8 miles from the Mexican mainland.\n\n==The Coronado Islands==\n\nThe Coronado Islands are a Mexican wildlife refuge; visitors may anchor, scuba, and snorkel, but trips ashore are not allowed.\n\n* '''North Coronado''' has no bay but boats can anchor on a jetty on the eastern side.\n**Location: {{coord|32|26.45|N|117|17.85|W|type:isle}}<ref name=\"Google Earth\">Google Earth</ref>\n**Size: {{convert|460000|m2|0|abbr=on}}\n**Height: {{convert|153|m|0|abbr=on}}\n**Length: {{convert|800|m|0|abbr=on}}\n* '''Pil\u00f3n de Az\u00facar''' (''Pile of Sugar'') is very difficult to land on. It has little vegetation but flocks of birds nest here.\n**Location: {{coord|32|25.45|N|117|15.75|W|type:isle}}<ref name=\"Google Earth\"/>\n**Size: {{convert|70000|m2|0|abbr=on}}\n**Height: {{convert|33|m|0|abbr=on}}\n* '''Central Coronado''' has a rocky peak with a heap of [[cactus]] and scrubs near the summit.\n**Location: {{coord|32|25.05|N|117|15.63|W|type:isle}}<ref name=\"Google Earth\"/>\n**Size: {{convert|140000|m2|0|abbr=on}}\n**Height: {{convert|32|m|0|abbr=on}}\n* '''South Coronado''' has the only bay of the islands, called 'Puerto Cueva' (\"Cave Port\"). There is a lighthouse at each end of the island.\n**Location: {{coord|32|24.5|N|117|14.75|W|type:isle}}<ref name=\"Google Earth\"/>\n**Size: {{convert|1.83|km2|0|abbr=on}}\n**Height: {{convert|220|m|0|abbr=on}}\n**Length: {{convert|3200|m|0|abbr=on}}<!-- this is a guess, 3.2 km) -->\n**Width: {{convert|800|m|0|abbr=on}}\n\n== History ==\nThe Coronado Islands are part of the [[municipality of Tijuana]], [[Baja California]], as ruled in the books of the Baja Californian Government, published on December 20, 1959:\n\n''Article 7 - the state of [[Baja California]] is divided and understood as the following municipalities .... Tijuana.''\n\n''c) The Municipality of [[Tijuana]] is made up of ..... in addition; The Coronado Islands correspond to the jurisdiction of the Municipality of Tijuana, which lie on the extremes of the municipality to the [[Pacific Ocean]].''\n\nIn September 1542 [[Juan Rodr\u00edguez Cabrillo]] described them as ''islas desiertas'' (desert islands). In 1602 the priest for [[Sebasti\u00e1n Vizca\u00edno]] called them ''Los Cuatro Coronados'' (the [[Four Crowned Martyrs|four crowned ones]]) to honour four martyrs. Although they have been called a dozen other names (later fisherman upon seeing floating coffins, ghostly faces and shrouded bodies amid the rocks dubbed them: Old Stone Face, The Sarcophagi, Dead Man's Island, and Corpus Christi) they also have been provocatively called ''The Sentries of San Diego Bay'' even though they belong to Mexico.\n\nIn October 1775, the Spanish Duque Miguel Eduardo de la Huerta from La Rioja (Northern Spain) came to the islands. The Duque had left his family on the kings request to obtain what Juan Cabrillo did not (gold from natives) . He saw the land of what Cabrillo called San Miguel ( now San Diego ) and continued to San Juan Capristrano. On the Island before he left, he wrote in the tress the names of his wife and children that he loved and missed ( Griselda and children Romalia and Sebastian) and never saw again. As he died in Dana Point April 1778. The trees are still on island now called Griselda. \n\nIn the 1920s and 1930s, during [[Prohibition in the United States]], the cove on the Northeast side of South Coronado Island was used as a meeting place for alcohol smugglers. Since it was the time before radar, and as foggy nights are common, the large number of boats frequently resulted in collisions. There was so much traffic that a famous casino flourished there until well into the Depression. Only the stone foundation remains though the name Smugglers Cove, and more rarely Casino Cove, adorn modern maps.\n\nIn May 1943 the [[U.S. Navy]]'s [[USS PC-815|USS ''PC-815'']], commanded by [[Military career of L. Ron Hubbard|L. Ron Hubbard]], conducted unauthorized gunnery exercises involving the shelling of the Coronado Islands, in the belief they were uninhabited and belonged to the United States. Unfortunately for Hubbard, the islands belonged to  Mexico and were occupied by the Mexican Coast Guard. The Mexican government complained and Hubbard was relieved of command.<ref>{{cite book | last = Miller | first = Russel | title = Bare-faced Messiah: The True Story of L. Ron Hubbard | url = https://archive.org/details/barefacedmessiah00mill_0 | url-access = registration | publisher = Henry Holt | year = 1988 | location = New York | pages = [https://archive.org/details/barefacedmessiah00mill_0/page/106 106\u2013107] | isbn = 1-55013-027-7}}</ref>\n\nThe islands are also a popular location for yellowtail fishing for San Diego fishermen.\n\n== Flora and fauna ==\n\nOn the North  and South Coronados there are [[Coreopsis maritima|sea dahlias]], various species of [[cactus]], [[marah macrocarpus|wild cucumber]] and [[Dudleya|houseleek]].\n\nThere are colonies of birds that nest on the islands and can be spotted in the nearby waters like [[gull]]s, [[cormorant]]s, [[pelican]]s, [[storm-petrel]]s, and [[alcid]]s. The Coronado Islands have the largest known colony of the rare [[Scripps's murrelet]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucsc.edu/news_events/text.asp?pid=1153 |title=UCSC graduate student's research leads to environmental victory in Coronado Islands |publisher=Ucsc.edu |date=2008-12-18 |accessdate=2009-07-25}}</ref> Pil\u00f3n de Az\u00facar, better known as Middle Rock, is host to the northernmost nesting colony of [[Brown booby|brown boobies]] on the west coast of North America.\n\nTen species of reptiles and amphibians are also found on the islands. The best known is the Coronado [[rattlesnake]] (''[[Crotalus oreganus caliginis]]''), which is a smaller subspecies than the one found on the mainland. There is also the [[Pituophis catenifer|Coronado Island gopher snake]], which feeds off birds' eggs, the [[Western skink|Coronado skink]], which is found on all four islands, and the [[arboreal salamander]]s which live on the three biggest islands.  [[Southern alligator lizard]]s are found on the north, south and central islands.<ref>{{cite journal |jstor=3889775|title=Food Habits of the San Diego Alligator Lizard |first=John D. |last=Cunningham |journal=Herpetologica |volume=12 |issue=3 |date=1956-09-01 |pages=225\u2013230}}</ref>\n\nThere are two types of mammals in the islands: rabbits and mice. How they reached the islands is currently unknown.\n\nSea mammals are plentiful and it is not uncommon to see groups of [[California sea lion]]s and [[Pinniped|seals]]. Middle Island is home to a small colony of [[northern elephant seal]]s.\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{citation |contributionurl=http://science.nature.nps.gov/im/units/medn/symposia/5th%20California%20Islands%20Symposium%20(1999)/Botany/Oberbauer_Vegetation_Flora_Los_Coronados_Island_Baja.pdf |contribution=Vegetation and Flora of Islas Los Coronados, Baja California, Mexico |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120722021744/http://science.nature.nps.gov/im/units/medn/symposia/5th%20California%20Islands%20Symposium%20(1999)/Botany/Oberbauer_Vegetation_Flora_Los_Coronados_Island_Baja.pdf |archivedate=July 22, 2012 |first1=Thomas A. |last1=Oberbauer |title=California Island Plant Distribution Patterns: Proceedings of the Fifth California Islands Symposium: 29 March to 1 April 1999 |publisher=Santa Barbara Museum of Natural History |place=Santa Barbara |pages=212\u2013223 |date=2002}}\n* http://www.sandiegogeologists.org/pub_download/1978_CoronadoIslandsBC.pdf\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.oceanlight.com/islas_coronado_mexico_photo.html Islas Coronado Mexico Photo Gallery]\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20120722175550/http://diver.net/seahunt/maps/coronodos.htm This links to a news article about the use of one of the islands as a waypoint for illegal migration to the United States. November 2010 [http://www.10news.com/news/25680019/detail.html]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Islands of Tijuana Municipality]]\n[[Category:Pacific islands of Mexico]]\n[[Category:California chaparral and woodlands]]\n[[Category:Islands of Baja California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other places|Coronado (disambiguation){{!}}Coronado}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2008}}\n[[File:Coronado Islands Map.jpg|440x440px|A map of the four Coronado Islands.|thumb]]\n[[File:800px-Islas Coronado.cc.jpg|thumb|300px|right|<center>The Coronado Islands, viewed from Tijuana beach</center>]]\n[[File:Border Patrol Vehicle near U.S. Mexico Border.jpg|thumb|At the US-Mexico border. The visible islands are Islas Coronado]] \nThe '''Coronado Islands''' (''Islas Coronado'' or ''Islas Coronados''; {{lang-en|Islands of the Coronation(s)}}) are a group of four [[island]]s off the northwest coast of the [[Mexico|Mexican]] [[States of Mexico|state]] of [[Baja California]]. Battered by the wind and waves, they are largely barren and uninhabited except for a small military detachment and a few lighthouse keepers. The islands lie between 15 and 19 miles south of the entrance to [[San Diego]] bay, but only 8 miles from the Mexican mainland.\n\n==The Coronado Islands==\n\nThe Coronado Islands are a Mexican wildlife refuge; visitors may anchor, scuba, and snorkel, but trips ashore are not allowed.\n\n* '''North Coronado''' has no bay but boats can anchor on a jetty on the eastern side.\n**Location: {{coord|32|26.45|N|117|17.85|W|type:isle}}<ref name=\"Google Earth\">Google Earth</ref>\n**Size: {{convert|460000|m2|0|abbr=on}}\n**Height: {{convert|153|m|0|abbr=on}}\n**Length: {{convert|800|m|0|abbr=on}}\n* '''Pil\u00f3n de Az\u00facar''' (''Pile of Sugar'') is very difficult to land on. It has little vegetation but flocks of birds nest here.\n**Location: {{coord|32|25.45|N|117|15.75|W|type:isle}}<ref name=\"Google Earth\"/>\n**Size: {{convert|70000|m2|0|abbr=on}}\n**Height: {{convert|33|m|0|abbr=on}}\n* '''Central Coronado''' has a rocky peak with a heap of [[cactus]] and scrubs near the summit.\n**Location: {{coord|32|25.05|N|117|15.63|W|type:isle}}<ref name=\"Google Earth\"/>\n**Size: {{convert|140000|m2|0|abbr=on}}\n**Height: {{convert|32|m|0|abbr=on}}\n* '''South Coronado''' has the only bay of the islands, called 'Puerto Cueva' (\"Cave Port\"). There is a lighthouse at each end of the island.\n**Location: {{coord|32|24.5|N|117|14.75|W|type:isle}}<ref name=\"Google Earth\"/>\n**Size: {{convert|1.83|km2|0|abbr=on}}\n**Height: {{convert|220|m|0|abbr=on}}\n**Length: {{convert|3200|m|0|abbr=on}}<!-- this is a guess, 3.2 km) -->\n**Width: {{convert|800|m|0|abbr=on}}\n\n== History ==\nThe Coronado Islands are part of the [[municipality of Tijuana]], [[Baja California]], as ruled in the books of the Baja Californian Government, published on December 20, 1959:\n\n''Article 7 - the state of [[Baja California]] is divided and understood as the following municipalities .... Tijuana.''\n\n''c) The Municipality of [[Tijuana]] is made up of ..... in addition; The Coronado Islands correspond to the jurisdiction of the Municipality of Tijuana, which lie on the extremes of the municipality to the [[Pacific Ocean]].''\n\nIn September 1542 [[Juan Rodr\u00edguez Cabrillo]] described them as ''islas desiertas'' (desert islands). In 1602 the priest for [[Sebasti\u00e1n Vizca\u00edno]] called them ''Los Cuatro Coronados'' (the [[Four Crowned Martyrs|four crowned ones]]) to honour four martyrs. Although they have been called a dozen other names (later fisherman upon seeing floating coffins, ghostly faces and shrouded bodies amid the rocks dubbed them: Old Stone Face, The Sarcophagi, Dead Man's Island, and Corpus Christi) they also have been provocatively called ''The Sentries of San Diego Bay'' even though they belong to Mexico.\n\nIn October 1775 , the Spanish Duque Miguel Eduardo de la Huerta from La Rioja (Northern Spain) came to the islands. The Duque had left his family on the kings request to obtain what Juan Cabrillo did not (gold from natives) . He saw the land of what Cabrillo called San Miguel ( now San Diego ) and continued to San Juan Capristrano. On the Island before he left, he wrote in the tress the names of his wife and children that he loved and missed ( Griselda and children Romalia and Sebastian) and never saw again. As he died in Dana Point April 1778. The trees are still on island now called Griselda. \n\nIn the 1920s and 1930s, during [[Prohibition in the United States]], the cove on the Northeast side of South Coronado Island was used as a meeting place for alcohol smugglers. Since it was the time before radar, and as foggy nights are common, the large number of boats frequently resulted in collisions. There was so much traffic that a famous casino flourished there until well into the Depression. Only the stone foundation remains though the name Smugglers Cove, and more rarely Casino Cove, adorn modern maps.\n\nIn May 1943 the [[U.S. Navy]]'s [[USS PC-815|USS ''PC-815'']], commanded by [[Military career of L. Ron Hubbard|L. Ron Hubbard]], conducted unauthorized gunnery exercises involving the shelling of the Coronado Islands, in the belief they were uninhabited and belonged to the United States. Unfortunately for Hubbard, the islands belonged to  Mexico and were occupied by the Mexican Coast Guard. The Mexican government complained and Hubbard was relieved of command.<ref>{{cite book | last = Miller | first = Russel | title = Bare-faced Messiah: The True Story of L. Ron Hubbard | url = https://archive.org/details/barefacedmessiah00mill_0 | url-access = registration | publisher = Henry Holt | year = 1988 | location = New York | pages = [https://archive.org/details/barefacedmessiah00mill_0/page/106 106\u2013107] | isbn = 1-55013-027-7}}</ref>\n\nThe islands are also a popular location for yellowtail fishing for San Diego fishermen.\n\n== Flora and fauna ==\n\nOn the North  and South Coronados there are [[Coreopsis maritima|sea dahlias]], various species of [[cactus]], [[marah macrocarpus|wild cucumber]] and [[Dudleya|houseleek]].\n\nThere are colonies of birds that nest on the islands and can be spotted in the nearby waters like [[gull]]s, [[cormorant]]s, [[pelican]]s, [[storm-petrel]]s, and [[alcid]]s. The Coronado Islands have the largest known colony of the rare [[Scripps's murrelet]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucsc.edu/news_events/text.asp?pid=1153 |title=UCSC graduate student's research leads to environmental victory in Coronado Islands |publisher=Ucsc.edu |date=2008-12-18 |accessdate=2009-07-25}}</ref> Pil\u00f3n de Az\u00facar, better known as Middle Rock, is host to the northernmost nesting colony of [[Brown booby|brown boobies]] on the west coast of North America.\n\nTen species of reptiles and amphibians are also found on the islands. The best known is the Coronado [[rattlesnake]] (''[[Crotalus oreganus caliginis]]''), which is a smaller subspecies than the one found on the mainland. There is also the [[Pituophis catenifer|Coronado Island gopher snake]], which feeds off birds' eggs, the [[Western skink|Coronado skink]], which is found on all four islands, and the [[arboreal salamander]]s which live on the three biggest islands.  [[Southern alligator lizard]]s are found on the north, south and central islands.<ref>{{cite journal |jstor=3889775|title=Food Habits of the San Diego Alligator Lizard |first=John D. |last=Cunningham |journal=Herpetologica |volume=12 |issue=3 |date=1956-09-01 |pages=225\u2013230}}</ref>\n\nThere are two types of mammals in the islands: rabbits and mice. How they reached the islands is currently unknown.\n\nSea mammals are plentiful and it is not uncommon to see groups of [[California sea lion]]s and [[Pinniped|seals]]. Middle Island is home to a small colony of [[northern elephant seal]]s.\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{citation |contributionurl=http://science.nature.nps.gov/im/units/medn/symposia/5th%20California%20Islands%20Symposium%20(1999)/Botany/Oberbauer_Vegetation_Flora_Los_Coronados_Island_Baja.pdf |contribution=Vegetation and Flora of Islas Los Coronados, Baja California, Mexico |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120722021744/http://science.nature.nps.gov/im/units/medn/symposia/5th%20California%20Islands%20Symposium%20(1999)/Botany/Oberbauer_Vegetation_Flora_Los_Coronados_Island_Baja.pdf |archivedate=July 22, 2012 |first1=Thomas A. |last1=Oberbauer |title=California Island Plant Distribution Patterns: Proceedings of the Fifth California Islands Symposium: 29 March to 1 April 1999 |publisher=Santa Barbara Museum of Natural History |place=Santa Barbara |pages=212\u2013223 |date=2002}}\n* http://www.sandiegogeologists.org/pub_download/1978_CoronadoIslandsBC.pdf\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.oceanlight.com/islas_coronado_mexico_photo.html Islas Coronado Mexico Photo Gallery]\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20120722175550/http://diver.net/seahunt/maps/coronodos.htm This links to a news article about the use of one of the islands as a waypoint for illegal migration to the United States. November 2010 [http://www.10news.com/news/25680019/detail.html]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Islands of Tijuana Municipality]]\n[[Category:Pacific islands of Mexico]]\n[[Category:California chaparral and woodlands]]\n[[Category:Islands of Baja California]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: ,  \u2192 ,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coronado_Islands"}
{"title_page": "Peter Mandelson", "text_new": "{{short description|British Labour politician}}\n{{redirect|Mandelson|the surname|Mandelson (surname)}}\n{{pp-move-dispute|small=yes}}\n{{use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Lord Mandelson\n| honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|PC}}\n| image = Peter Mandelson, September 2008.jpg\n| office = [[First Secretary of State]]\n| primeminister = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| term_start = 5 June 2009\n| term_end = 11 May 2010\n| predecessor = [[John Prescott]] (2007){{Ref label|aaa|a}}\n| successor = [[William Hague]]\n| office1 = [[Lord President of the Council]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| term_start1 = 5 June 2009\n| term_end1 = 11 May 2010\n| predecessor1 = [[Janet Royall, Baroness Royall of Blaisdon|The Baroness Royall of Blaisdon]]\n| successor1 = [[Nick Clegg]]\n| office2 = [[Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills]]<ref>Business, Enterprise and Regulatory Reform (2008\u201309)</ref> <br/>[[President of the Board of Trade]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| term_start2 = 3 October 2008\n| term_end2 = 11 May 2010\n| predecessor2 = [[John Hutton, Baron Hutton of Furness|John Hutton]]\n| successor2 = [[Vince Cable]]\n| office6 = [[European Commissioner for Trade]]\n| nominator6 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| president6 = [[Jos\u00e9 Manuel Barroso]]\n| term_start6 = 22 November 2004\n| term_end6 = 3 October 2008\n| predecessor6 = [[Pascal Lamy]]\n| successor6 = [[Catherine Ashton]]\n| office7 = [[Secretary of State for Northern Ireland]]\n| primeminister7 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| term_start7 = 11 October 1999\n| term_end7 = 24 January 2001\n| predecessor7 = [[Mo Mowlam]]\n| successor7 = [[John Reid, Baron Reid of Cardowan|John Reid]]\n| office8 = [[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|Secretary of State for Trade and Industry]]<br/>[[President of the Board of Trade]]\n| primeminister8 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| term_start8 = 27 July 1998\n| term_end8 = 23 December 1998\n| predecessor8 = [[Margaret Beckett]]\n| successor8 = [[Stephen Byers]]\n| office9 = [[Minister without portfolio|Minister without Portfolio]]\n| primeminister9 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| term_start9 = 2 May 1997\n| term_end9 = 27 July 1998\n| predecessor9 = [[Brian Mawhinney, Baron Mawhinney|Brian Mawhinney]]\n| successor9 = [[Charles Clarke]]\n| office10 = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lord Temporal]]\n| term_start10 = 13 October 2008<br>[[Life peer]]age\n| office11 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br>for [[Hartlepool (UK Parliament constituency)|Hartlepool]]\n| term_start11 = 9 April 1992\n| term_end11 = 8 September 2004\n| predecessor11 = [[Ted Leadbitter]]\n| successor11 = [[Iain Wright]]\n| birth_name = Peter Benjamin Mandelson\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1953|10|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Hampstead Garden Suburb]], [[London]], England\n| death_date = \n| signature = Signature of Peter Mandelson.png\n| death_place = \n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] (1973\u2013present)<br > [[Communist Party of Great Britain|Communist Party]] (1967-1973)\n| partner = Reinaldo Avila da Silva\n| alma_mater = [[St Catherine's College, Oxford]]\n| footnotes = a. {{note|aaa}}Office vacant from 27 June 2007 to 5 June 2009.\n}}\n'''Peter Benjamin Mandelson, Baron Mandelson''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|PC}} (born 21 October 1953) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] politician, president of international think tank [[Policy Network]], and chairman of strategic advisory firm Global Counsel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theguardian.com/politics/peter-mandelson |title=Peter Mandelson {{!}} Politics |website=The Guardian |language=en |access-date=2018-09-03}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1985 to 1991, Mandelson served as Labour's [[Director of communications|Director of Communications]]. He was one of the first to whom the term '[[Spin (propaganda)|spin doctor]]' was applied and gained the nickname 'the [[Prince of Darkness (Satan)|Prince of Darkness]]' because of his 'ruthlessness' and 'media savvy'.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Swaine|first=Jon|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/3127802/Peter-Mandelson-profile-The-Prince-of-Darkness-returns.html|title=Peter Mandelson profile: The Prince of Darkness returns|date=2008-10-03|access-date=2020-03-30|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> He served as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Hartlepool (UK Parliament constituency)|Hartlepool]] from [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]] to [[2004 Hartlepool by-election|2004]] and held a number of [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|Cabinet]] positions under [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Ministers]] [[Tony Blair]] and [[Gordon Brown]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-mandelson/500 |title=Lord Mandelson |website=UK Parliament |language=en |access-date=2018-09-03}}</ref> He was the [[European Commissioner for Trade]] between 2004 and 2008.\n\nMandelson was one of several key individuals responsible for the rebranding of the Labour Party as [[New Labour]] before its subsequent victory in the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 election]].<ref name=bbc-profile>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7650195.stm|title=Profile: Peter Mandelson|work=BBC News|date=3 October 2008|accessdate=13 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/apr/29/new-labour-20-years-on-tony-blair-david-miliband-peter-mandelson-alastair-campbell|title='What do we do now?': the New Labour landslide, 20 years on|last=Freedland|first=Jonathan|date=2017-04-29|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-02-26|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> He was twice forced to resign from the Cabinet before leaving Parliament to take up an appointment as a European Commissioner. He later rejoined the Cabinet for a third time after being created a [[Life Peer]], sitting on the Labour benches in the [[House of Lords]]. He is the only person to hold the position of [[First Secretary of State]] as a Peer.<ref>{{cite news |publisher=BBC News |date=13 October 2008 |accessdate=29 October 2008 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7666482.stm |title=Baron Mandelson joins the Lords}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n===Family===\nPeter Mandelson was born in [[Hampstead Garden Suburb]], [[Middlesex]],<ref>http://tria.fcampalans.cat/images/{{dead link |date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}/mandelson_prospect.pdf</ref> on 21 October 1953,<ref name=bbc-profile/> the son of Mary Joyce (''[[n\u00e9e]]'' Morrison) and George Norman Mandelson.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/the-mandelson-loan-mystery-of-the-pounds-475000-townhouse-1193990.html |newspaper=The Independent |first1=Steve |last1=Boggan |first2=Paul |last2=Waugh |date=23 December 1998 |title=The Mandelson loan: Mystery of the pounds 475,000 townhouse}}</ref> His father's family were Jewish; his grandfather had founded the Harrow United Synagogue. His father (known as Tony) was the advertising manager of ''[[The Jewish Chronicle]]''<ref name=jc-20100722>{{cite news |url=http://www.thejc.com/lifestyle/lifestyle-features/36025/mandelson-judaism-lord-levy-and-his-jc-dad |title=Mandelson on Judaism, Lord Levy and his JC dad |author=Jenni Frazer |newspaper=The Jewish Chronicle |date=22 July 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2015}}</ref> who was commissioned as an [[Officer (armed forces)|officer]] in the [[1st The Royal Dragoons|Royal Dragoons]] in the [[Second World War]].<ref name=ThirdMan>{{cite book |last=Mandelson |first=Peter |title=The Third Man: Life at the Heart of New Labour |year=2010 |publisher=HarperPress |isbn=978-0007395286}}</ref> On his mother's side, Mandelson is a grandson of [[Herbert Morrison]], the [[London County Council]] Leader and Labour Cabinet Minister in the [[Attlee ministry]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thepeerage.com/p41260.htm#i412596 |title=Person Page 41260 |publisher=The peerage |accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe says of his childhood - \"my whole upbringing was framed around the Suburb - my friendships and values\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hamhigh.co.uk/etcetera/paradise-found-peter-mandelson-recalls-growing-up-on-the-suburb-1-626468 |title=Paradise found: Peter Mandelson recalls growing up on the Suburb |website=Hampstead Highgate Express |language=en |access-date=2019-02-26}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\nMandelson attended Garden Suburb School<ref name=\"ThirdMan\" /> and between 1965 and 1972 [[Hendon School|Hendon County Grammar School]].<ref name=\"bbc-profile\" /> In 1966 he appeared on stage with the local amateur theatre group, the [[Garden Suburb Theatre|Hampstead Garden Suburb Dramatic Society]], as the eponymous lead in ''[[The Winslow Boy]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/a-life-less-ordinary-1088534.html |title=A life less ordinary |last=Macintyre |first=Donald |date=21 April 1999 |newspaper=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1973 to 1976 he read [[Philosophy, Politics and Economics]] at [[St Catherine's College, Oxford]]. During his teenage years he was a member of the [[Young Communist League (UK)|Young Communist League]],<ref name=\"bbc-profile\" /> but later became a member of the [[Oxford University Labour Club]].\n\n== Early career ==\nIn the late 1970s he became Chairman of the [[British Youth Council]]. As Chair of the BYC, he was a delegate in 1978 to the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]]-organised [[World Festival of Youth and Students]] in [[Havana]], Cuba. There, with several future Labour Cabinet colleagues, he \u2013 together with future IUSY President Hilary Barnard, [[Charles Clarke]], [[Richard Corbett]] and [[Trevor Phillips]] \u2013 successfully frustrated agreement on a distorted Soviet text on youth in the capitalist countries.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2003/aug/28/cuba.world |title=Revolution revisited |last=Wilson |first=Brian |date=28 August 2003 |newspaper=The Guardian |authorlink=Brian Wilson (Labour politician) |accessdate=16 July 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2003/jan/19/labour.race |title=Race winner |last=Ahmed |first=Kamal |date=19 January 2003 |newspaper=The Observer |accessdate=16 July 2008}}</ref>\n\nHe was elected to [[Lambeth Borough Council]] in September 1979 but stood down in 1982, disillusioned with the state of Labour politics.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/mar/01/peter-mandelson-interview-royal-mail |title=On his return, Mandelson shows he's ready to fight |newspaper=The Guardian |date=1 March 2009 |accessdate=27 November 2009 |first=Andrew |last=Rawnsley}}</ref>\n\nMandelson then worked for some time as a television producer at [[London Weekend Television]] on ''[[Weekend World]]'', where he formed a friendship with his superior [[John Birt, Baron Birt|John (''now'' Lord) Birt]].\n\n== Political career ==\n\n=== Labour's Director of Communications ===\nIn 1985, the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] leader [[Neil Kinnock]] appointed him as the party's Director of Communications. As Director, he was one of the first people in Britain to whom the term \"[[spin (public relations)|spin doctor]]\" was applied; he was thus called \"the [[Satan|Prince of Darkness]]\".<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/peter-mandelson-prince-of-darkness-who-travels-the-world-spreading-the-gospel-for-new-labour-595112.html |title=Peter Mandelson: 'Prince of Darkness' who travels the world spreading the gospel for New Labour \u2013 Profiles, People |newspaper=The Independent |date=21 April 2003 |accessdate=13 April 2010 |first=Andrew |last=Grice}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/404194.stm |title='Prince of darkness' returns |publisher=BBC News |date=12 October 1999 |accessdate=13 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986 Mandelson ran the campaign at the [[1986 Fulham by-election|Fulham by-election]] in which Labour defeated the Conservative Party.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/labour/3129952/Peter-Mandelson-Timeline-of-his-career.html|title=Peter Mandelson: Timeline of his career|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=3 October 2008|accessdate=26 April 2010 | location=London|first=Jon|last=Swaine}}</ref> For the [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987 election campaign]], Mandelson commissioned film director [[Hugh Hudson]], whose ''[[Chariots of Fire]]'' (1981) had won an [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Oscar as Best Picture]], to make a [[party political broadcast]] promoting [[Neil Kinnock]] as a potential prime minister. Tagged \"Kinnock \u2013 the Movie\", it led to the party leader's approval rating being raised by 16%<ref name=\"Fielding\">Steven Fielding [http://www.screenonline.org.uk/tv/id/1390778/index.html \"Labour Party Election Broadcast (21 May 1987)\"], BFI screenonline</ref> or 19% in polls<ref name=\"Walker\">Tim Walker [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9399091/Why-Chariots-of-Fire-director-Hugh-Hudson-wont-make-broadcasts-for-Ed-Miliband.html \"Why Chariots of Fire director Hugh Hudson won't make broadcasts for Ed Miliband\"], The Telegraph, 14 July 2012</ref> and was even repeated in another PPB slot.<ref name=\"Fielding\" /> The election, held on 11 June 1987, returned [[Margaret Thatcher]]'s [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] for the third time, although Labour gained 20 seats,<ref name=\"BBC19\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-10518842|work=BBC News |title=The rise and fall of New Labour|date=3 August 2010}}</ref> and, this time, convincingly pushed the SDP-Liberal Alliance into third place. Opponents termed the Labour Party's election campaign \"a brilliantly successful election defeat\".<ref name=\"Walker\" />\n\nHe ceased being a Labour Party official in 1991 when he was selected as Labour [[Prospective parliamentary candidate|candidate]] for the safe [[constituency|seat]] of [[Hartlepool (constituency)|Hartlepool]].\n\n[[Malcolm Tucker]], the fictional character from [[Armando Iannucci]]'s ''[[The Thick of It]]'', is based, in part, on Mandelson.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dee|first=Johnny|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2009/oct/17/peter-capaldi-malcolm-tucker-tv|title=Peter Capaldi: Malcolm Tucker is Alastair Campbell. But Mandelson is in there, too|date=2009-10-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-30|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n===As an MP===\nMandelson was first elected to the [[United Kingdom House of Commons|House of Commons]] at the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]],<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=52903|page=7176|date=24 April 1992\n}}</ref> and made several speeches outlining his strong support for the [[European Union]]. Although sidelined during the brief period when [[John Smith (Labour Party leader)|John Smith]] led the party, Mandelson was by now close to two [[Shadow Cabinet]] members \u2013 [[Gordon Brown]] and [[Tony Blair]] \u2013 each regarded as potential future [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|leaders of the party]].\n\nFollowing Smith's sudden death on 12 May 1994, Mandelson chose to back Blair for the leadership, believing him to be a superior communicator to Brown<ref name=\"Blair story\">{{cite news|title=The Tony Blair Story|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6506365.stm|work=BBC News|date=10 May 2007|accessdate=23 September 2008}}</ref> and played a leading role in the leadership campaign. This created antagonism between Mandelson and Brown, though they were considered allies in the Labour Party.<ref name=\"it's love\">{{cite news|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/uk-politics/2009/06/mandelson-brown-blair-prime |title=Brown and Mandelson: It's Love|newspaper=New Statesman|accessdate=13 April 2010}}</ref> In 1994 [[Kate Garvey]] suggested that Mandelson (who was at the time being derided by the trade unions and other Labour factions), should adopt a \"[[nom de guerre]]\" throughout Blair's leadership bid, so that he might conceal his considerable role within the campaign team. Mandelson agreed to be called \"Bobby\" for the duration and was thanked by Blair using this name in his victory speech.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=_v8LAQAAMAAJ&q=%22kate+garvey%22+mandelson+bobby&dq=%22kate+garvey%22+mandelson+bobby|authorlink=Cherie Blair |page=173 |title=Speaking for myself: The autobiography |isbn=9781408700983 |last1=Blair |first1=Cherie |year=2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nextleft.org/2010/08/peter-breaks-cover-again-as-blairite.html |title=Peter breaks cover (again) as the Blairite battalions come out }}</ref>\n\nAfter becoming a close ally and trusted adviser to [[Tony Blair]], Mandelson was Labour's election campaign director for the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]], which Labour won decisively.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/commentators/peter-mandelson-labours-election-campaign-needs--to-express-its-vision-and-beliefs-684602.html|title=Peter Mandelson: Labour's election campaign needs to express its vision and beliefs|newspaper=The Independent|location=UK|accessdate=12 August 2009|date=14 May 2001 }}</ref>\n\n=== Minister without Portfolio ===\nHe was appointed as a [[Minister without Portfolio]] in the [[Cabinet Office]], where his job was to co-ordinate within government. A few months later, he also acquired responsibility for the [[Millennium Dome]], after Blair decided to go ahead with the project despite the opposition of most of the cabinet (including the [[Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport]] who had been running it). [[Jennifer Page (Millenium Dome)|Jennie Page]], the Dome project's chief executive, was abruptly sacked after a farcical opening night.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/topics/people/Lord_Mandelson|title=Peter Mandelson|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-09-03}}</ref> She gave evidence to a House of Commons Select Committee for Culture and Heritage in June 2000. In what was seen as a reference to the close interest in the Dome from Mandelson, known at the time as so-called \"Dome Secretary\" and his successor [[Lord Falconer of Thoroton]], Page told the committee: \"I made several attempts to persuade ministers that standing back from the Dome would be good for them as well as good for the Dome\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Page told ministers to stay away from Dome', ''The Independent''|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/this-britain/page-told-ministers-to-stay-away-from-dome-715271.html|accessdate=31 July 2008|location=London|first=Severin|last=Carrell|date=16 June 2000}}</ref>\n\nIn July 1998 he was appointed to the Cabinet as [[Secretary of State for Trade and Industry]]; he launched the [[Y2K|Millennium Bug And Electronic Commerce Bill]] and a Competitiveness [[White Paper]], which he described, as 'bold, far reaching and absolutely necessary'. He also appointed a \"[[Internet|Net]] Tsar\" to lead the UK in what he termed the \"new industrial revolution\". In 1998 he was appointed a [[Privy Counsellor]].\n\nMandelson bought a home in [[Notting Hill]] in 1996 partly with an interest-free loan of \u00a3373,000 from [[Geoffrey Robinson]], a cabinet colleague and millionaire whose business dealings were subject to an inquiry by Mandelson's department.<ref name=\"resignation1\">{{cite news |title=Double resignation rocks government |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/241464.stm |work=BBC News |date=23 December 1998 |accessdate=13 February 2007}}</ref> Mandelson contended that he had deliberately not taken part in any decisions relating to Robinson. However, he had not declared the loan in the [[Register of Members' Interests]] and resigned in December 1998.<ref name=\"resignation1\" /> Mandelson had also not declared the loan to his building society (the [[Britannia Building Society|Britannia]]) although they decided not to take any action, with the CEO stating \"I am satisfied that the information given to us at the time of the mortgage application was accurate.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Mandelson gets mortgage all-clear |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/251125.stm|work=BBC News|date=8 January 1999|accessdate=13 February 2007}}</ref> Mandelson initially thought he could weather the press storm, but had to resign when it became clear that the Prime Minister thought nothing else would clear the air.<ref>{{cite news|authorlink=Andrew Rawnsley|last=Rawnsley|first=Andrew |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=17 September 2000|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2000/sep/17/mandelson.labour2|title=The house comes tumbling down |location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2000 it was reported that Robinson had \"accused Peter Mandelson of lying to the Commons about the home loan affair that cost both of them their government jobs.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Brogan|first=Benedict |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1370559/Mandelson-lied-over-home-loan.html |title=Mandelson 'lied over home loan' |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=16 October 2000|accessdate=13 April 2010 |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/mandelson-lied-over-loan-634660.html|title=Mandelson 'lied' over loan|newspaper=The Independent|location=London|date=16 October 2000}}</ref>\n\n=== Secretary of State for Northern Ireland ===\nHe was out of the Cabinet for ten months. In October 1999 he was appointed [[Secretary of State for Northern Ireland]], replacing [[Mo Mowlam]]. In his very first speech in the post he mistakenly referred to himself as the \"Secretary of State for Ireland.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Mandelson passes first Commons test|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/480695.stm|work=BBC News|date=20 October 1999|accessdate=13 February 2007}}</ref> During his tenure he oversaw the creation of the [[Northern Ireland Assembly|devolved legislative assembly]] and [[Northern Ireland Executive|power-sharing executive]] and reform of the [[Police Service of Northern Ireland|police service]].\n\nOn 24 January 2001 Mandelson resigned from the [[UK Government|Government]] for a second time, following accusations of using his position to influence a passport application.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/1134819.stm |title=Mandelson resigns over Hinduja affair |work=BBC News|date= 24 January 2001|accessdate=3 October 2008}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=56106|page=1223|date=31 January 2001}}</ref> He had contacted [[Home Office]] Minister [[Mike O'Brien (UK politician)|Mike O'Brien]] on behalf of [[Hindujas|Srichand Hinduja]], an Indian businessman who was seeking British citizenship and whose family firm was to become the main sponsor of the \"Faith Zone\" in the [[Millennium Dome]]. At the time Hinduja and his brothers were under investigation by the Indian government for alleged involvement in the [[Bofors scandal]]. Mandelson insisted he had done nothing wrong and was exonerated by an independent inquiry by Sir Anthony Hammond, which concluded that neither Mandelson nor anyone else had acted improperly. The front-page headline in ''[[The Independent]]'' read in part \"Passport to Oblivion\".<ref>Andrew Grice, \"The Mandelson Resignation: Passport to Oblivion\", ''The Independent'', 25 January 2001</ref>\n\nAt the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]] Mandelson was challenged by [[Arthur Scargill]] of the [[Socialist Labour Party (UK)|Socialist Labour Party]] and by John Booth, a former Labour Party press officer standing as \"Genuine Labour\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/1314307.stm|title=Mandelson faces new challenger|date=5 May 2001|work=BBC News |accessdate=5 April 2009}}</ref> but Mandelson was re-elected with a large majority.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://politics.guardian.co.uk/hoc/constituency/0,,-1005,00.html |title=Hartlepool |last=Ask Aristotle |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=5 April 2009 |location=London |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090312051426/http://politics.guardian.co.uk/hoc/constituency/0%2C%2C-1005%2C00.html |archivedate=12 March 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> This prompted him to make an exuberant acceptance speech, which was televised live, in which he declared that \"I'm a fighter, not a quitter\"<ref name=\"bbc-profile\" /> and referred to his \"inner steel\".\n\n=== Stepping down as MP ===\nDespite Labour success in the June 2001 general election, a third Cabinet appointment did not materialise and he indicated his interest in becoming the United Kingdom's [[European Commissioner]] when the new [[European Commission|Commission]] was established in 2004. Both of Britain's Commissioners, [[Neil Kinnock]] and [[Chris Patten]], were due to stand down. Appointment as a European Commissioner would require his resignation from Parliament precipitating a [[by-election]] in his Hartlepool constituency. His appointment was announced in the summer and on 8 September 2004 Mandelson resigned his seat by submitting his name as [[Steward of the Manor of Northstead]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.scotsman.com/petermandelson/Mandelson-appointed-to-lead-EU.2554339.jp|title=Mandelson appointed to lead EU trade|newspaper=The Scotsman|location=UK|date=17 August 2004|accessdate=28 November 2009|first=James|last=Kirkup}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=57414 |page=11832|date=20 September 2004\n}}</ref> Labour won the subsequent [[2004 Hartlepool by-election|Hartlepool by-election]] with a much-reduced majority of 2,033 votes (equating to 40.7% of the vote).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2004/oct/01/uk.byelections|title=Tories pushed into fourth place as Labour holds on to Hartlepool|newspaper=The Guardian |location=UK |date=1 October 2004|accessdate=28 November 2009|first=Patrick|last=Wintour}}</ref> He was succeeded as MP for Hartlepool by [[Iain Wright]].\n\n=== European Commissioner ===\nOn 22 November 2004 Mandelson became Britain's European Commissioner, taking the [[European Commissioner for Trade|trade portfolio]].\n\nIn October 2008 he left his post as Trade Commissioner to return to UK politics. As a former EU Commissioner, Lord Mandelson is entitled to a \u00a331,000 pension when he reaches the age of 65 years. This however is contingent on a \"duty of loyalty to the Communities\", which applies also after his term in office.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/4996440/Lord-Mandelson-must-remain-loyal-to-EU-to-guarantee-pension.html|title=Lord Mandelson must remain loyal to EU to guarantee pension|last=Editor|first=Christopher Hope, Whitehall|date=2009-03-16|access-date=2018-09-03|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> The [[Taxpayers' Alliance]], which uncovered the threat to his pension, demanded that he should declare the conflict of interest and either relinquish his EU pay cheques or resign as a [[minister (diplomacy)|minister]]. \"When one considers that his new ministerial post deals specifically with business, enterprise and regulatory reform \u2013 all areas that are intimately involved with EU legislation, regulation and policy \u2013\" the group said, \"the conflict of interest is even more stark.\" Mandelson did not agree that he had a conflict of interests. \"He has always had a clear view of British interests and how they are secured by our EU membership,\" a spokesperson said.<ref>Christopher Hope: [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/labour/4996440/Lord-Mandelson-must-remain-loyal-to-EU-to-guarantee-pension.html Lord Mandelson must remain loyal to EU to guarantee pension] ''The Daily Telegraph'', 16 March 2009.</ref>\n\n===Peerage and return to Cabinet===\n[[File:Gordon Brown and Peter Mandelson.jpg|right|thumb|Mandelson (left) with [[Gordon Brown]] at the Progressive Governance Conference, February 2010.]]\nOn 3 October 2008, as part of [[Gordon Brown]]'s Cabinet reshuffle, it was announced amid some controversy<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/news/legal-and-constitutional/mandelson-becomes-peer-amid-controversy-$1244576.htm |title=Mandelson becomes peer amid controversy |publisher=Politics|accessdate=13 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Nicholas Watt|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/oct/13/mandelson-lords |title=Peter Mandelson goes to Lords amid new controversy|newspaper=The Guardian|location=UK|date=13 October 2008|accessdate=13 April 2010}}</ref> that Mandelson would return to [[Her Majesty's Government|Government]] in the re-designated post of [[Secretary of State for Business, Enterprise and Regulatory Reform|Business Secretary]] and would be raised to the [[life peer|peerage]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/3127802/Peter-Mandelson-profile-The-Prince-of-Darkness-returns.html|title=Peter Mandelson profile: The Prince of Darkness returns|last=Swaine|first=Jon|date=2008-10-03|access-date=2019-02-26|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> thus becoming a [[member of the House of Lords]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7650013.stm|title= Mandelson to return to government|work=BBC News|accessdate=3 October 2008 | date=3 October 2008}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=58848 |page=15551|date=10 October 2008 }}</ref> On 13 October 2008 he was created '''Baron Mandelson''', of [[Foy, Herefordshire|Foy]] in the County of [[Herefordshire]] and of [[Hartlepool]] in the County of [[County Durham|Durham]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=58855 |page=15991 |date=17 October 2008}}</ref> and was [[Introduction (House of Lords)|introduced]] in the [[House of Lords]] the same day.<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200708/minutes/081014/ldordpap.htm#minproc House of Lords Minute of Proceedings of Monday 13 October 2008].</ref>\n\nFollowing his return to office, Mandelson supported [[Expansion of London Heathrow Airport|the planned Heathrow expansion]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23601732-mandelson-throws-his-weight-behind-third-heathrow-runway.do|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130505090244/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23601732-mandelson-throws-his-weight-behind-third-heathrow-runway.do|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 May 2013|title=Mandelson throws his weight behind third Heathrow runway|newspaper=London Evening Standard|date=15 December 2008|accessdate=27 November 2009}}</ref> On 6 March 2009, environmental protester [[Leila Deen]] of anti-aviation group [[Plane Stupid]] approached him outside a summit on the government's low carbon industrial strategy and threw a cup of green custard in his face in protest over his support for a third runway at Heathrow Airport. The protester was cautioned on 9 April for causing \"harassment, alarm or distress\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/7991907.stm |title=Mandelson custard woman cautioned|date=9 April 2009 |work=BBC News|accessdate=15 April 2009}}</ref><ref>Hines, Nico: [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article5856186.ece Protester throws green custard in the face of Lord Mandelson and walks away] ''The Times'', 6 March 2009</ref>\n\nIn a Cabinet reshuffle on 5 June 2009 Mandelson was granted the honorific title of [[First Secretary of State]] and appointed [[Lord President of the Council]];<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/jun/05/cabinet-reshuffle-gordon-brown-ed-balls|title=Weakened Gordon Brown unable to shift cabinet's bigger beasts|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=5 June 2008|location=London|first=Patrick|last=Wintour}}</ref> it was also announced that the [[Department for Innovation, Universities and Skills]] would be merged into his, giving him the new title of [[Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills]] and that he would continue as [[President of the Board of Trade]].<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\" /><ref>[http://number10.gov.uk/ Full list of Cabinet members], Prime Minister's Office, 5 June 2009</ref>\n\nMandelson was a member of 35 of the 43 Cabinet committees and subcommittees.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/5882622/Lord-Mandelsons-empire-35-Cabinet-committee-posts.html| newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|title=Lord Mandelson's empire: 35 Cabinet committee posts|first=Murray|last=Wardrop | date=22 July 2009|accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2009 Mandelson was widely reported to have ordered \"technical measures\" such as internet disconnection to be included in the draft of the [[Digital Economy Act 2010]] after a \"big lobbying operation\", even though the [[Digital Britain]] report had rejected this type of punishment.<ref name=\"timesAug2009\">{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article6809329.ece|first=Sam|last=Coates|title=Families could lose broadband access as Mandelson takes on web pirates|newspaper=Times|date=26 August 2009|accessdate=21 April 2011|location=London}}</ref> ''[[The Independent]]'' reported that according to their Whitehall sources, Mandelson was persuaded that tough laws were needed to reduce online copyright infringement following an intensive lobbying campaign by influential people in the music and film industry.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/the-net-closes-in-on-internet-piracy-1772820.html|title=The Net closes in on internet piracy|newspaper=The Independent|date=16 August 2009|accessdate=25 November 2009|location=London}}</ref> The paper also reported that this included a meeting with [[DreamWorks Pictures|DreamWorks]] co-founder [[David Geffen]] at the [[Rothschild]] family villa on the Greek island of Corfu. Mandelson's spokesperson claimed that there had been no discussion of internet piracy during the Corfu dinner and suggested that the decision to reverse Lord Carter's findings had been taken in late July before the trip. ''[[The Times]]'' reported after the Corfu meeting that an unnamed Whitehall source had confirmed that before this trip, Mandelson had shown little personal interest in the Digital Britain agenda, which has been ongoing for several years. According to the source of ''The Times'', Mandelson returned from holiday and effectively issued an edict that the regulation needed to be tougher.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://technology.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/tech_and_web/the_web/article6797844.ece|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110403114449/http://technology.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/tech_and_web/the_web/article6797844.ece|archivedate=3 April 2011|title=Mandelson targets web pirates after dinner with mogul|newspaper=The Times|date=16 August 2009|accessdate=6 January 2009|location=London|first=Jonathan|last=Oliver}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2011 a [[Freedom of information in the United Kingdom|Freedom of Information]] (FOI) request showed that Mandelson had decided to approve the inclusion of technical measures, such as the disconnection of internet access, at least two months before public consultation had finished and that he had shown little interest in the consultation. Letters from Mandelson's office document talks with [[Lucian Grainge]], CEO of [[Universal Music Group]] on 2 June 2009 and that on the following day Mandelson advised [[Stephen Carter, Baron Carter of Barnes|Lord Carter]] about the \"possibility of [the Secretary of State] having a power to direct Ofcom to go directly to introduce technical measures\". Mandelson made the formal announcement that technical measures, including disconnection, were to be included in the Digital Economy Bill two months later on 7 August 2009.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wilson|first=Dean| title=Documents show the Digital Economy Act was a done deal all along| publisher=The Inquirer| date=1 August 2011|url= http://www.theinquirer.net/inquirer/news/2098344/documents-digital-economy-act-deal| accessdate=14 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nAn opinion poll conducted by the centre-left think tank [[Compass (think tank)|Compass]] found in March 2009 that Mandelson was less disliked by party members than Deputy Leader [[Harriet Harman]]. This was felt to be unusual as Mandelson \"historically has been unpopular among Labour members\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/labour/4953559/Harriet-Harman-less-popular-than-Peter-Mandelson-among-Labour-members.html|title= Harriet Harman less popular than Peter Mandelson among Labour members |work=Telegraph webside|accessdate=8 March 2009 | location=London | first=Patrick | last=Hennessy | date=7 March 2009}}</ref> [[Tony Blair]]'s assertion in 1996 that \"my project will be complete when the Labour Party learns to love Peter Mandelson\"<ref>cited in ''The Daily Telegraph'', 2 March 1996, [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/3750847.stm \"Blair: In his own words\"], BBC News Channel, 11 May 2007</ref> was seen as prophetic in late September 2009 when Mandelson was enthusiastically received at the [[Labour Party (UK) Conference|party conference]] in Brighton.<ref>Ben Wright [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8279705.stm \"Labour learns to love Mandelson\"], BBC ''News at Ten'', 28 September 2009</ref>\n\n== Post-Cabinet career ==\nAfter the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] lost the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], Mandelson's memoirs, ''[[The Third Man: Life at the Heart of New Labour]]'', were published in July 2010, two months after leaving office.<ref>Andrew Rawnsley [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2010/jul/18/peter-mandelson-third-man-memoirs \"''The Third Man'' by Peter Mandelson\"], ''The Observer'', 18 July 2010</ref><ref>Matthew d'Ancona [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/7906908/The-Third-Man-by-Peter-Mandelson-review.html \"''The Third Man'' by Peter Mandelson: review\"], ''The Daily Telegraph'', 28 July 2010</ref> The memoirs were subsequently criticised by Labour leadership contenders [[Ed Miliband|Ed]] and [[David Miliband]] and [[Andy Burnham]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-10671510 |work=BBC News|title=Mandelson memoirs condemned by Labour leadership rivals |date=17 July 2010}}</ref> During this time he was appointed President of the international think tank [[Policy Network]].\n\nIn November 2010, Mandelson and [[Benjamin Wegg-Prosser]] founded [[Global Counsel]], a consultancy firm based in London, with the financial support of WPP, the advertising giant.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/8169875/Lord-Mandelson-to-head-classy-consultancy-firm.html |location=London |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |first=Nick |last=Collins |title=Lord Mandelson to head 'classy' consultancy firm |date=30 November 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"ft-20130531\">{{cite news |url=http://blogs.ft.com/westminster/2013/05/mandelson-looks-east-for-russian-directorship/ |title=Mandelson looks east for Russian directorship |author=Jim Pickard |newspaper=Financial Times |date=31 May 2013 |accessdate=9 August 2013}}</ref> The firm provides advice for [[Strategic management|corporate strategists and senior management]] worldwide. Mandelson has been criticised for so far not disclosing his clients.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/Politics/article1534435.ece?CMP=OTH-gnws-standard-2015_03_22|title=Mandelson faces having to name business clients|date=22 March 2015|newspaper=The Sunday Times|accessdate=30 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, 2008, 2009, 2011, 2012, 2013 and 2014 Mandelson was an invited guest of the [[Bilderberg Group]] and attended the annual conferences.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199900/cmregmem/memi19.htm|title=British House of Commons \u2013 Register of Journalists' Interests|publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom|author=House of Commons|accessdate=13 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/blog/2009/may/19/bilderberg-skelton-greece|title=Our man at Bilderberg|last=Skelton|first=Charlie|date=19 May 2009|work=The Guardian|location=UK|quote=Mandelson's office has confirmed his attendance at this year's meeting: \"Yes, Lord Mandelson attended Bilberberg. He found it a valuable conference.\"|accessdate=20 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2011, it was announced that Mandelson would serve as a senior adviser to the advisory investment banking firm, [[Lazard]].<ref>{{cite news |publisher=Lazard, Ltd. |title=Press Release: Lord Mandelson to Serve as a Senior Adviser to Lazard |url=http://www.lazard.com/PDF/Lazard%20-%20Mandelson%201-21-2011.pdf |accessdate=11 March 2011 |date=21 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713192049/http://www.lazard.com/PDF/Lazard%20-%20Mandelson%201-21-2011.pdf |archivedate=13 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"telegraph-20110821\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/8714791/Mandelson-poised-to-buy-8m-home.html|title=Mandelson poised to buy \u00a38m home|date=21 August 2011|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|author=Holly Watt|accessdate=20 January 2015}}</ref> In 2013, he also joined the Board of Trustees of [[Deutsche Bank]]'s Alfred Herrhausen Gesellschaft.<ref>[https://www.alfred-herrhausen-gesellschaft.de/en/kuratorium.htm Board of Trustees] Alfred Herrhausen Gesellschaft of [[Deutsche Bank]].</ref> In May 2011 it was revealed that there was speculation that Mandelson had been approached by [[China]] to be a candidate for the leadership of the [[International Monetary Fund]], even though Mandelson had not been a [[finance minister]] or headed a [[central bank]]. However, it was then speculated that Mandelson would stand to succeed [[Pascal Lamy]] as Director-General of the [[World Trade Organization]], backed by [[David Cameron]].\n\nIn May 2012, Mandelson confirmed that he was advising [[Asia Pulp & Paper]] (APP) in selling timber products to Europe. In 2012 APP was accused of [[illegal logging]] in [[Indonesia]] and damaging the habitats of rare animals such as the [[Sumatran tiger]]. At least 67 companies worldwide, such as [[Tesco]] and [[Kraft Foods]] since 2004 and [[Danone]] since 2012 have boycotted APP.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/may/10/mandelson-advises-company-rainforest Lord Mandelson confirms he is advising company accused of illegal logging] Peer's consultancy works for paper and pulp multinational alleged to have chopped down protected trees Guardian 10 May 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.greenpeace.org/international/en/news/Blogs/makingwaves/yoghurt-for-forests-danone-drops-asia-pulp-an/blog/39818/ Yoghurt for forests! Danone drops Asia Pulp and Paper, plans zero deforestation policy] [[Greenpeace]] 2 April 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.greenpeace.org/international/Global/international/publications/forests/2012/Indonesia/Greenpeace_TRPT_report.docx The Ramin Paper Trail Asia Pulp & Paper Under Investigation \u2013 Part 2] [http://www.greenpeace.org/international/en/publications/Campaign-reports/Forests-Reports/The-Ramin-Paper-Trail in short] [[Greenpeace]] 1 March 2012</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Mandelson was appointed to the revived post of [[High Steward of Hull]], a ceremonial position held by his grandfather [[Herbert Morrison]] in 1956\u201365 and defunct [[Local Government Act 1972|since 1974]].<ref name=\"bbc21290844\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-humber-21290844|title=East Yorkshire city brings back ancient roles|work=BBC News|accessdate=19 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Labour leadership of Jeremy Corbyn===\nAfter the [[2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2015 Labour leadership election]] resulted in [[Jeremy Corbyn]] becoming the [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|party leader]], Mandelson stated that he believed that Labour was now unelectable, but advised party members unhappy with the situation to wait for Corbyn to demonstrate this before working to replace him.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34355545 |title=Lord Mandelson: Don't rush to oust Jeremy Corbyn |work=BBC News |date=25 September 2015|accessdate=27 July 2016}}</ref> He wished for an early general election to force Corbyn out.<ref name=guardian-20160927>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/sep/27/peter-mandelson-i-am-praying-for-early-election |title=Peter Mandelson 'praying' for early election to end 'awful' Labour saga |last=Weaver |first=Matthew |newspaper=The Guardian |date=27 September 2016 |accessdate=16 June 2017}}</ref> In February 2017, he said Corbyn had \"no idea in the 21st century how to conduct himself as a leader of a party putting itself forward in a democratic election\" and \"I work every single day to bring forward the end of [Corbyn's] tenure in office\".<ref name=telegraph-20170221>{{cite news|last=Hughes|first=Laura|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/02/21/lord-mandelson-working-every-single-day-bring-end-jeremy-corbyns/ |title=Lord Mandelson: I am working 'every single day' to bring an end to Jeremy Corbyn's leadership |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=21 February 2017 |accessdate=21 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter the results of the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]] became known, Mandelson conceded that Corbyn's election campaign was \"very sure footed\" and the result, in which Labour gained seats and denied the Conservatives a majority, unexpected.<ref>{{cite news|last=Merrick|first=Rob|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/r-a7782766.html|title=Jeremy Corbyn strengthens his grip on the Labour party as harshest critics change their tune|work=The Independent|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=16 June 2017}}</ref> \"I was wrong\" about Corbyn, he told BBC News. \"I am very surprised, an earthquake has happened in British politics and I did not foresee it\", although he doubted Corbyn's ability to gain a Commons majority.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mairs|first=Nicholas|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/jeremy-corbyn/news/86571/i-was-clearly-wrong-jeremy-corbyns|title='I was clearly wrong' - Jeremy Corbyn's Labour critics congratulate the leader|work=Politics Home|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=16 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Remain Campaign ==\nDuring the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 EU referendum]], Mandelson sat on the board on [[Britain Stronger in Europe|Britain Stronger IN Europe]], the official \"Remain\" campaign. The campaign was unsuccessful.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/98619e5c-3f70-11e6-8716-a4a71e8140b0|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-02-26}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the referendum, Mandelson was an outspoken supporter of a [[People's Vote]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/final-say-peter-mandelson-brexit-referendum-peoples-vote-theresa-may-tory-cornservatives-a8469666.html|title=Fresh Brexit referendum could empower Theresa May to 'stand up against Brextremists' blackmail', says Peter Mandelson|date=2018-07-30|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-02-26}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\nDuring the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal|2009 expenses scandal]] ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' raised questions about the timing of Mandelson's second home allowance claim, dating from 2004, saying, \"Lord Mandelson billed the taxpayer for almost \u00a33,000 of work on his constituency home in Hartlepool less than a week after announcing his decision to stand down as an MP.\" Mandelson said in a statement, \"The work done was necessary maintenance. All claims made were reasonable and submitted consistent with parliamentary rules.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5293035/MPs-expenses-Questions-over-timing-of-Peter-Mandelsons-house-claim.html|title=MPs expenses: Questions over timing of Peter Mandelson's house claim|last=Prince|first=Rosa|date=8 May 2009|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|accessdate=18 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 April 2005 ''[[The Times]]'' revealed that Mandelson had spent the previous New Year's Eve on the yacht of [[Paul Allen]], the co-founder of [[Microsoft]], which was at the centre of a major EU investigation and although it did not allege impropriety, it did state that Mandelson's visit was inappropriate for a serving European Commissioner.<ref>Anthony Browne, Daniel McGrory and Lewis Smith [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/europe/article384041.ece \"Mandelson, the computer king and a party on a luxury yacht\",] ''The Times'', 22 April 2009</ref>\n\nDuring the summer of 2008 Mandelson had a widely publicised disagreement with [[Nicolas Sarkozy]], [[President of France]].<ref name=\"bbc-profile\" /> Sarkozy accused him of trying to sell out European farmers and appeared to blame his handling of the Doha round of trade talks for the \"no\" vote in the [[Twenty-eighth Amendment of the Constitution Bill, 2008 (Ireland)|Irish referendum]] on the [[Treaty of Lisbon]]. Mandelson said his position at world trade talks had been undermined and told the [[BBC]] he did not start the row, saying, \"I stood up for myself, I'm not to be bullied.\" He said he believed the row was over but renewed his warnings on [[protectionism]].<ref name=\"bbc-profile\" />\n\nIn 2008 Mandelson was hospitalised, suffering from a kidney stone. At this time, [[melamine]] added to [[2008 Chinese milk scandal|milk in China]] had caused kidney stones and other ailments in thousands of Chinese children, killing at least six. Ironically, during the previous week Mandelson had drunk a glass of Chinese yoghurt in front of reporters in order to show his confidence in Chinese dairy products, although his own kidney stones were unrelated.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/labour/3144271/Peter-Mandelson-to-have-kidney-stone-removed.html|title=Peter Mandelson to have kidney stone removed|date=6 October 2008|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|location=UK|author=Jon Swaine|accessdate=7 September 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/archive/news/mandelson-ill-after-yoghurt-in-china/story-e6frg6t6-1111117689177?nk=8ce946fc6104191a0524d770da72f62c|title=British politician Peter Mandelson ill after yoghurt in China|date=8 October 2008|work=The Australian|author=Rowan Callick|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2008 Mandelson was reported to have maintained private contacts over several years with Russian oligarch [[Oleg Deripaska]], most recently on holiday in August 2008 on Deripaska's yacht at Taverna Agni on the Greek island of [[Corfu]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article4982163.ece|title=Lord Mandelson and Oleg Deripaska dined together 'a year before they met'|last=Robertson|first=David|date=21 October 2008|newspaper=The Times|location=UK|accessdate=23 October 2008}}</ref> News of the contacts sparked criticism because, as European Union Trade Commissioner, Mandelson had been responsible for two decisions to cut aluminium tariffs that had benefited Deripaska's United Company [[RusAl]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.moscowtimes.ru/article/1010/42/371829.htm|title=UK. Conservatives Linked to Deripaska|date=22 October 2008|newspaper=[[The Moscow Times]]|accessdate=23 October 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081126051311/http://www.moscowtimes.ru/article/1010/42/371829.htm|archivedate=26 November 2008}}</ref> Mandelson denied that there had been a [[conflict of interest]] and insisted that he had never discussed aluminium tariffs with Deripaska.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article4932191.ece|title=Peter Mandelson dogged by his links to Russian oligarch|date=13 October 2008|newspaper=The Times|last2=Charter|first2=David|location=UK|accessdate=23 October 2008|first1=David|last1=Robertson}}</ref> On 26 October 2008 the [[Shadow Foreign Secretary]] [[William Hague]] claimed the \"whole country\" wanted \"transparency\" about Mandelson's previous meetings with Deripaska. In response, Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]] said Mandelson's dealings with Deripaska had been \"found to be above board\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7691678.stm|title=Tories seek Mandelson 'clarity'|date=26 October 2008|work=BBC News|accessdate=30 October 2008}}</ref> Mandelson said that meeting business figures from \"across the range\" in emerging economies was part of his brief as EU Trade Commissioner.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/oct/28/peter-mandelson-oleg-deripaska-corfu|title=Mandelson silent on Deripaska|last=Parfitt|first=Tom|date=28 October 2008|newspaper=The Guardian|location=UK|accessdate=30 October 2008}}</ref> On 29 October 2008, while Mandelson was on a ministerial visit to Moscow,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/oct/29/russia-mandelson|title=Mandelson hails thaw in relations with Moscow|last=Parfitt|first=Tom|date=29 October 2008|newspaper=The Guardian|location=UK|accessdate=30 October 2008}}</ref> it was alleged in the British press that [[Valery Pechyonkin|Valery Pechenkin]], the head of security at Deripaska's company Basic Element, had organised a swift entry visa for Mandelson when he turned up in [[Moscow]] to visit Deripaska in 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23579423-details/Veteran+KGB+spy+revealed+as+Deripaska%27s+right-hand+man/article.do|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081101053919/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23579423-details/Veteran+KGB+spy+revealed+as+Deripaska%27s+right-hand+man/article.do|url-status=dead|archive-date=1 November 2008|title=Veteran KGB spy revealed as Deripaska's right-hand man|date=29 October 2008|newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]]|accessdate=30 October 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2013, writing for the [[Progress (organisation)|Progress website]], Mandelson warned Labour it risked harming its election chances if [[affiliated trade unions]] continued to \"manipulate parliamentary selections\" as was alleged in the [[2013 Labour Party Falkirk candidate selection]] controversy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.progressonline.org.uk/2013/06/27/no-more-falkirks/|title=No more Falkirks|publisher=progressonline.org.uk|accessdate=19 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/jun/27/labour-mandelson-unions-unite-legal-falkirk | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Patrick | last=Wintour | title=Unite threatens Labour with legal action over Falkirk row | date=27 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2014 it was reported that Mandelson had strong ties to Russian conglomerate [[Sistema]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/10744744/Peter-Mandelson-refuses-to-defend-links-to-Russian-defence-firm.html|title=Peter Mandelson refuses to defend links to Russian defence firm|date=4 April 2014|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=19 August 2015|last1=Holehouse|first1=Matthew}}</ref>\n\n== Non-political commitments ==\nMandelson was until 8 October 2008 the President of [[Central School of Speech and Drama]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmregmem/memi19.htm|title=The House of Commons \u2013 Register of Members' Interests|publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom|author=House of Commons|accessdate=13 April 2010}}</ref> He was replaced in this un-remunerated post by playwright [[Harold Pinter]], who died two months later.\n\nIn 2011, Mandelson was guest of honour at Herbert Morrison Primary School in Vauxhall, South London. The school was hosting a special themed day in honour of Mandelson's grandfather, Herbert Morrison, after whom the school was named.\n\n==Personal life==\n\n=== Partner and sexuality ===\nMandelson is gay and he is said to be 'intensely private' about his personal life.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/the-truth-was-out-and-so-were-the-knives-1088357.html|title=The truth was 'out'. And so were the knives|date=1999-04-20|newspaper=The Independent|access-date=2017-02-21|language=en-GB}}</ref> During his time as a former government leader, the press \u2013 tabloid and broadsheet alike \u2013 often portrayed Mandelson as effeminate through \"the linguistic resources of camp\" (as evidenced through his common nickname, 'Mandy') and narcissistic \u2013 sometimes including coded references to homosexual acts in their descriptions of his actions.<ref>Morrish, L. (2002) '\"That's so typical of Peter \u2013 as soon as there's a cock-up he tries to sit on it\": British Broadsheet Press versus Peter Mandleson 1996\u2013 2001.' Paper given at the ''9th Annual American University Conference on Lavender Languages and Linguistics''.</ref>\n\nHe has lived with his life partner Reinaldo Avila da Silva, a [[Brazilians|Brazilian-British]] translator, since March 1998.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/4258915/Is-stricken-Mandy-likely-to-lose-Reinaldo-too.html|title=Is stricken Mandy likely to lose Reinaldo, too?|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=2017-02-21|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Attempted outings and harassment ===\nWhile his sexual orientation was known to friends, colleagues and constituents, in 1987 the ''[[News of the World]]'' ran an issue that attempted to out Mandelson as gay.<ref name=\":0\" /> Mandelson preferred to keep his personal life private and as such did not respond.<ref name=\"Tatchell-1998\">{{cite news|url=http://www.petertatchell.net/celebrities/petermandelson/|title=Why Mandy Won't Let Sexuality Queer the Pitch|date=31 January 1998|work=Punch|last1=Tatchell|first1=Peter|authorlink1=Peter Tatchell}}</ref> Mandelson was outed again by [[Matthew Parris]] in 1998 on the BBC programme ''[[Newsnight]]''.<ref name=\"BBC-2010\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-10973463|title=BBC to replay clip of Lord Mandelson being 'outed'|date=14 August 2010|work=BBC News}}</ref> This led to press harassment of his partner, with the ''[[Daily Express]]'' sending a reporter to take pictures of him while he was at his languages course.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nAn internal investigation later found that the photos had been obtained without Avila da Silva's consent and images of him attempting to cover his face had been secretly deleted. Mandelson phoned the BBC and the [[Press Complaints Commission]] following ''Newsnight''{{'s}} broadcast,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/mandelson-phoned-bbc-after-being-outed-1.212032|title=Mandelson phoned BBC after being 'outed'|date=7 November 1998|work=The Irish Times}}</ref> and an internal memo was later sent within the BBC, stating that \"Under no circumstances whatsoever should allegations about the private life of Peter Mandelson be repeated or referred to on any broadcast.\"<ref name=\"BBC-2010\" />\n\n==In the media==\n* [[BBC Four]]'s ''[[Storyville (TV series)|Storyville]]'' in 2010, ''Mandelson: The Real PM?'', directed by [[Hannah Mary Rothschild|Hannah Rothschild]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00w4k2d |title=Storyville, 2010\u20132011, Mandelson: The Real PM? |publisher=BBC Four |date=28 November 2010 |accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref> a [[fly on the wall]] documentary about Mandelson as Business Secretary in the run up to the 2010 general election.\n* Mandelson was portrayed by [[Mark Gatiss]] in the 2015 [[Channel 4]] drama ''[[Coalition (film)|Coalition]]''.\n* Mandelson was portrayed by [[Nigel Planer]] in the 2011 comedy drama ''[[The Hunt for Tony Blair]]''.\n* The ''[[Little Britain]]'' character [[List of Little Britain characters#Sebastian Love|Sebastian Love]] was based on Mandelson\n\n==Honours==\n* [[Image:Legion Honneur Officier ribbon.svg|45px]] Officer, [[Legion of Honour|L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\nHe was made an Officier of the [[Legion of Honour]] in February 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mandelson receives French Legion d'honneur|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-38845392|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=3 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* (with [[Roger Liddle]]) ''The Blair Revolution: Can New Labour Deliver?'' Faber, 1996 {{ISBN|978-0571178186}} ; ''The Blair Revolution Revisited'', (2nd ed), Politicos, 2002, {{ISBN|978-1842750391}}\n* (contributor) ''[[The City in Europe and the World]]'', European Research Forum at London Metropolitan University, 2006 {{ISBN|978-0954744816}}\n* ''The Third Man: Life at the Heart of New Labour'' Harper Press, 2010 {{ISBN|978-0007395286}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Jones, Nicholas (2000): ''Sultans of Spin: The Media and the New Labour Government'' Orion Books, {{ISBN|0-7528-2769-3}}\n* [[Donald Macintyre (journalist)|Macintyre, Donald]] (1999): ''Mandelson: The Biography'' Harper Collins, {{ISBN|0-00-255943-9}}\n* [[Andrew Rawnsley|Rawnsley, Andrew]] (2001): ''Servants of the People: The Inside Story of New Labour'' Penguin Books, {{ISBN|0-14-027850-8}}\n* Routledge, Paul (1999): ''Mandy: The Unauthorised Biography of Peter Mandelson'' Simon & Schuster, {{ISBN|0-684-85175-X}}\n* [[Anthony Seldon|Seldon, Anthony]] (2005): ''Blair'' The Free Press, {{ISBN|0-7432-3212-7}}\n\n===Works===\n* Mandelson, Peter (1997): ''[http://digital.library.lse.ac.uk/objects/lse:boc326get Labour's next steps]'' Fabian Society\n* Mandelson, Peter (2002): ''The Blair Revolution Revisited'' Politico's, {{ISBN|1-84275-039-9}}\n* {{cite book|last=Mandelson|first=Peter|title=The Third Man: Life at the Heart of New Labour|year=2010|publisher=HarperPress|isbn=978-0007395286}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Peter Mandelson}}\n* [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/peer/10412/lord_mandelson Lord Mandelson, former MP - They Work For You] \n* [https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-mandelson/500 Peter Mandelson profile at UK Parliament]\n* [https://www.ft.com/topics/people/Lord_Mandelson Peter Mandelson | Financial Times]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170914202340/http://www.policy-network.net/ Policy Network]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/7650195.stm Profile: Peter Mandelson] ''[[BBC News]]'', 3 October 2008, [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/3916089.stm 13 August 2004]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111004230954/http://www.publicaffairsasia.com/publicaffairsasia/FeatureView.do?id=97 Peter Mandelson: Interview in full], PublicAffairsAsia.com, 18 August 2008, on sovereign wealth funds\n* [http://www.newstatesman.com/uk-politics/2008/10/labour-party-mandelson-brown Peter Mandelson: Interview] on [[New Statesman]], 1 October 2008.\n* {{C-SPAN|petermandelson}}\n* {{Charlie Rose view|3211}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120418062306/http://www.policy-network.net/content/350/socialdemocracyobservatory Social Democracy Observatory]\n* {{IMDb name|1128320}}\n* {{Worldcat id|lccn-n97-817}}\n* {{Guardian topic}}\n* {{NYTtopic|people/m/peter_mandelson}}\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/peter-mandelson Peter Mandelson | Politics | The Guardian]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ted Leadbitter]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br>for [[Hartlepool (UK Parliament constituency)|Hartlepool]]|years=[[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]]\u2013[[2004 Hartlepool by-election|2004]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Iain Wright]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Brian Mawhinney, Baron Mawhinney|Brian Mawhinney]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister without portfolio#United Kingdom|Minister without Portfolio]]|years=1997\u20131998}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Charles Clarke]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Margaret Beckett]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|Secretary of State for Trade and Industry]]|years=1998}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Stephen Byers]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mo Mowlam]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for Northern Ireland]]|years=1999\u20132001}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John Reid, Baron Reid of Cardowan|John Reid]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Pascal Lamy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[European Commissioner for Trade]]|years=2004\u20132008}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Catherine Ashton]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Hutton, Baron Hutton of Furness|John Hutton]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|Secretary of State for Business, Innovation Skills]]|years=2008\u20132010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Vince Cable]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Prescott]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[First Secretary of State]]|years=2009\u20132010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[William Hague]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Janet Royall, Baroness Royall of Blaisdon|The Baroness Royall]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Lord President of the Council]]|years=2009\u20132010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Nick Clegg]]}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Igor Judge|The Lord Judge]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Orders of precedence in the United Kingdom|Gentlemen]]'''<br />''Baron Mandelson'' '''}}\n{{s-fol|after=[[Paul Myners|The Lord Myners]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Brown Cabinet}}\n{{First Secretary of State}}\n{{Presidents of the Board of Trade}}\n{{First Barroso Commission}}\n{{Secretaries of State for Northern Ireland}}\n{{European Commissioners from the United Kingdom}}\n{{European Commissioner for Trade}}\n{{New Labour}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mandelson, Peter}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Advocates of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Catherine's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British European Commissioners]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Lambeth]]\n[[Category:English socialists]]\n[[Category:English male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:English people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:English political writers]]\n[[Category:First Secretaries of State of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) officials]]\n[[Category:LGBT life peers]]\n[[Category:LGBT members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from England]]\n[[Category:Lord Presidents of the Council]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:New Labour]]\n[[Category:People educated at Hendon School]]\n[[Category:People from Hendon]]\n[[Category:Politics of the Borough of Hartlepool]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of State for Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1992\u20131997]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:Writers from London]]\n[[Category:Officiers of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Board of Trade]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Labour politician}}\n{{redirect|Mandelson|the surname|Mandelson (surname)}}\n{{pp-move-dispute|small=yes}}\n{{use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Lord Mandelson\n| honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|PC}}\n| image = Peter Mandelson, September 2008.jpg\n| office = [[First Secretary of State]]\n| primeminister = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| term_start = 5 June 2009\n| term_end = 11 May 2010\n| predecessor = [[John Prescott]] {{small|(2007){{Ref label|aaa|a}}}}\n| successor = [[William Hague]]\n| office1 = [[Lord President of the Council]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| term_start1 = 5 June 2009\n| term_end1 = 11 May 2010\n| predecessor1 = [[Janet Royall, Baroness Royall of Blaisdon|The Baroness Royall of Blaisdon]]\n| successor1 = [[Nick Clegg]]\n| office2 = [[Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills]]<ref>Business, Enterprise and Regulatory Reform (2008\u201309)</ref> <br/>[[President of the Board of Trade]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| term_start2 = 3 October 2008\n| term_end2 = 11 May 2010\n| predecessor2 = [[John Hutton, Baron Hutton of Furness|John Hutton]]\n| successor2 = [[Vince Cable]]\n| office6 = [[European Commissioner for Trade]]\n| nominator6 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| president6 = [[Jos\u00e9 Manuel Barroso]]\n| term_start6 = 22 November 2004\n| term_end6 = 3 October 2008\n| predecessor6 = [[Pascal Lamy]]\n| successor6 = [[Catherine Ashton]]\n| office7 = [[Secretary of State for Northern Ireland]]\n| primeminister7 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| term_start7 = 11 October 1999\n| term_end7 = 24 January 2001\n| predecessor7 = [[Mo Mowlam]]\n| successor7 = [[John Reid, Baron Reid of Cardowan|John Reid]]\n| office8 = [[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|Secretary of State for Trade and Industry]]<br/>[[President of the Board of Trade]]\n| primeminister8 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| term_start8 = 27 July 1998\n| term_end8 = 23 December 1998\n| predecessor8 = [[Margaret Beckett]]\n| successor8 = [[Stephen Byers]]\n| office9 = [[Minister without portfolio|Minister without Portfolio]]\n| primeminister9 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| term_start9 = 2 May 1997\n| term_end9 = 27 July 1998\n| predecessor9 = [[Brian Mawhinney, Baron Mawhinney|Brian Mawhinney]]\n| successor9 = [[Charles Clarke]]\n| office10 = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lord Temporal]]\n| term_start10 = 13 October 2008<br>[[Life peer]]age\n| office11 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br>for [[Hartlepool (UK Parliament constituency)|Hartlepool]]\n| term_start11 = 9 April 1992\n| term_end11 = 8 September 2004\n| predecessor11 = [[Ted Leadbitter]]\n| successor11 = [[Iain Wright]]\n| birth_name = Peter Benjamin Mandelson\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1953|10|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Hampstead Garden Suburb]], [[London]], England\n| death_date = \n| signature = Signature of Peter Mandelson.png\n| death_place = \n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] (1973\u2013present)<br > [[Communist Party of Great Britain|Communist Party]] (1967-1973)\n| partner = Reinaldo Avila da Silva\n| alma_mater = [[St Catherine's College, Oxford]]\n| footnotes = <small> a. {{note|aaa}}Office vacant from 27 June 2007 to 5 June 2009. </small>\n}}\n'''Peter Benjamin Mandelson, Baron Mandelson''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|PC}} (born 21 October 1953) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] politician, president of international think tank [[Policy Network]], and chairman of strategic advisory firm Global Counsel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theguardian.com/politics/peter-mandelson |title=Peter Mandelson {{!}} Politics |website=The Guardian |language=en |access-date=2018-09-03}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1985 to 1991, Mandelson served as Labour's [[Director of communications|Director of Communications]]. He was one of the first to whom the term '[[Spin (propaganda)|spin doctor]]' was applied and gained the nickname 'the [[Prince of Darkness (Satan)|Prince of Darkness]]' because of his 'ruthlessness' and 'media savvy'.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Swaine|first=Jon|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/3127802/Peter-Mandelson-profile-The-Prince-of-Darkness-returns.html|title=Peter Mandelson profile: The Prince of Darkness returns|date=2008-10-03|access-date=2020-03-30|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> He served as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Hartlepool (UK Parliament constituency)|Hartlepool]] from [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]] to [[2004 Hartlepool by-election|2004]] and held a number of [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|Cabinet]] positions under [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Ministers]] [[Tony Blair]] and [[Gordon Brown]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-mandelson/500 |title=Lord Mandelson |website=UK Parliament |language=en |access-date=2018-09-03}}</ref> He was the [[European Commissioner for Trade]] between 2004 and 2008.\n\nMandelson was one of several key individuals responsible for the rebranding of the Labour Party as [[New Labour]] before its subsequent victory in the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 election]].<ref name=bbc-profile>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7650195.stm|title=Profile: Peter Mandelson|work=BBC News|date=3 October 2008|accessdate=13 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/apr/29/new-labour-20-years-on-tony-blair-david-miliband-peter-mandelson-alastair-campbell|title='What do we do now?': the New Labour landslide, 20 years on|last=Freedland|first=Jonathan|date=2017-04-29|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-02-26|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> He was twice forced to resign from the Cabinet before leaving Parliament to take up an appointment as a European Commissioner. He later rejoined the Cabinet for a third time after being created a [[Life Peer]], sitting on the Labour benches in the [[House of Lords]]. He is the only person to hold the position of [[First Secretary of State]] as a Peer.<ref>{{cite news |publisher=BBC News |date=13 October 2008 |accessdate=29 October 2008 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7666482.stm |title=Baron Mandelson joins the Lords}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n===Family===\nPeter Mandelson was born in [[Hampstead Garden Suburb]], [[Middlesex]],<ref>http://tria.fcampalans.cat/images/{{dead link |date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}/mandelson_prospect.pdf</ref> on 21 October 1953,<ref name=bbc-profile/> the son of Mary Joyce (''[[n\u00e9e]]'' Morrison) and George Norman Mandelson.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/the-mandelson-loan-mystery-of-the-pounds-475000-townhouse-1193990.html |newspaper=The Independent |first1=Steve |last1=Boggan |first2=Paul |last2=Waugh |date=23 December 1998 |title=The Mandelson loan: Mystery of the pounds 475,000 townhouse}}</ref> His father's family were Jewish; his grandfather had founded the Harrow United Synagogue. His father (known as Tony) was the advertising manager of ''[[The Jewish Chronicle]]''<ref name=jc-20100722>{{cite news |url=http://www.thejc.com/lifestyle/lifestyle-features/36025/mandelson-judaism-lord-levy-and-his-jc-dad |title=Mandelson on Judaism, Lord Levy and his JC dad |author=Jenni Frazer |newspaper=The Jewish Chronicle |date=22 July 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2015}}</ref> who was commissioned as an [[Officer (armed forces)|officer]] in the [[1st The Royal Dragoons|Royal Dragoons]] in the [[Second World War]].<ref name=ThirdMan>{{cite book |last=Mandelson |first=Peter |title=The Third Man: Life at the Heart of New Labour |year=2010 |publisher=HarperPress |isbn=978-0007395286}}</ref> On his mother's side, Mandelson is a grandson of [[Herbert Morrison]], the [[London County Council]] Leader and Labour Cabinet Minister in the [[Attlee ministry]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thepeerage.com/p41260.htm#i412596 |title=Person Page 41260 |publisher=The peerage |accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe says of his childhood - \"my whole upbringing was framed around the Suburb - my friendships and values\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hamhigh.co.uk/etcetera/paradise-found-peter-mandelson-recalls-growing-up-on-the-suburb-1-626468 |title=Paradise found: Peter Mandelson recalls growing up on the Suburb |website=Hampstead Highgate Express |language=en |access-date=2019-02-26}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\nMandelson attended Garden Suburb School<ref name=\"ThirdMan\" /> and between 1965 and 1972 [[Hendon School|Hendon County Grammar School]].<ref name=\"bbc-profile\" /> In 1966 he appeared on stage with the local amateur theatre group, the [[Garden Suburb Theatre|Hampstead Garden Suburb Dramatic Society]], as the eponymous lead in ''[[The Winslow Boy]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/a-life-less-ordinary-1088534.html |title=A life less ordinary |last=Macintyre |first=Donald |date=21 April 1999 |newspaper=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1973 to 1976 he read [[Philosophy, Politics and Economics]] at [[St Catherine's College, Oxford]]. During his teenage years he was a member of the [[Young Communist League (UK)|Young Communist League]],<ref name=\"bbc-profile\" /> but later became a member of the [[Oxford University Labour Club]].\n\n== Early career ==\nIn the late 1970s he became Chairman of the [[British Youth Council]]. As Chair of the BYC, he was a delegate in 1978 to the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]]-organised [[World Festival of Youth and Students]] in [[Havana]], Cuba. There, with several future Labour Cabinet colleagues, he \u2013 together with future IUSY President Hilary Barnard, [[Charles Clarke]], [[Richard Corbett]] and [[Trevor Phillips]] \u2013 successfully frustrated agreement on a distorted Soviet text on youth in the capitalist countries.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2003/aug/28/cuba.world |title=Revolution revisited |last=Wilson |first=Brian |date=28 August 2003 |newspaper=The Guardian |authorlink=Brian Wilson (Labour politician) |accessdate=16 July 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2003/jan/19/labour.race |title=Race winner |last=Ahmed |first=Kamal |date=19 January 2003 |newspaper=The Observer |accessdate=16 July 2008}}</ref>\n\nHe was elected to [[Lambeth Borough Council]] in September 1979 but stood down in 1982, disillusioned with the state of Labour politics.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/mar/01/peter-mandelson-interview-royal-mail |title=On his return, Mandelson shows he's ready to fight |newspaper=The Guardian |date=1 March 2009 |accessdate=27 November 2009 |first=Andrew |last=Rawnsley}}</ref>\n\nMandelson then worked for some time as a television producer at [[London Weekend Television]] on ''[[Weekend World]]'', where he formed a friendship with his superior [[John Birt, Baron Birt|John (''now'' Lord) Birt]].\n\n== Political career ==\n\n=== Labour's Director of Communications ===\nIn 1985, the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] leader [[Neil Kinnock]] appointed him as the party's Director of Communications. As Director, he was one of the first people in Britain to whom the term \"[[spin (public relations)|spin doctor]]\" was applied; he was thus called \"the [[Satan|Prince of Darkness]]\".<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/peter-mandelson-prince-of-darkness-who-travels-the-world-spreading-the-gospel-for-new-labour-595112.html |title=Peter Mandelson: 'Prince of Darkness' who travels the world spreading the gospel for New Labour \u2013 Profiles, People |newspaper=The Independent |date=21 April 2003 |accessdate=13 April 2010 |first=Andrew |last=Grice}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/404194.stm |title='Prince of darkness' returns |publisher=BBC News |date=12 October 1999 |accessdate=13 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986 Mandelson ran the campaign at the [[1986 Fulham by-election|Fulham by-election]] in which Labour defeated the Conservative Party.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/labour/3129952/Peter-Mandelson-Timeline-of-his-career.html|title=Peter Mandelson: Timeline of his career|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=3 October 2008|accessdate=26 April 2010 | location=London|first=Jon|last=Swaine}}</ref> For the [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987 election campaign]], Mandelson commissioned film director [[Hugh Hudson]], whose ''[[Chariots of Fire]]'' (1981) had won an [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Oscar as Best Picture]], to make a [[party political broadcast]] promoting [[Neil Kinnock]] as a potential prime minister. Tagged \"Kinnock \u2013 the Movie\", it led to the party leader's approval rating being raised by 16%<ref name=\"Fielding\">Steven Fielding [http://www.screenonline.org.uk/tv/id/1390778/index.html \"Labour Party Election Broadcast (21 May 1987)\"], BFI screenonline</ref> or 19% in polls<ref name=\"Walker\">Tim Walker [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9399091/Why-Chariots-of-Fire-director-Hugh-Hudson-wont-make-broadcasts-for-Ed-Miliband.html \"Why Chariots of Fire director Hugh Hudson won't make broadcasts for Ed Miliband\"], The Telegraph, 14 July 2012</ref> and was even repeated in another PPB slot.<ref name=\"Fielding\" /> The election, held on 11 June 1987, returned [[Margaret Thatcher]]'s [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] for the third time, although Labour gained 20 seats,<ref name=\"BBC19\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-10518842|work=BBC News |title=The rise and fall of New Labour|date=3 August 2010}}</ref> and, this time, convincingly pushed the SDP-Liberal Alliance into third place. Opponents termed the Labour Party's election campaign \"a brilliantly successful election defeat\".<ref name=\"Walker\" />\n\nHe ceased being a Labour Party official in 1991 when he was selected as Labour [[Prospective parliamentary candidate|candidate]] for the safe [[constituency|seat]] of [[Hartlepool (constituency)|Hartlepool]].\n\n[[Malcolm Tucker]], the fictional character from [[Armando Iannucci]]'s ''[[The Thick of It]]'', is based, in part, on Mandelson.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dee|first=Johnny|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2009/oct/17/peter-capaldi-malcolm-tucker-tv|title=Peter Capaldi: Malcolm Tucker is Alastair Campbell. But Mandelson is in there, too|date=2009-10-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-30|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n===As an MP===\nMandelson was first elected to the [[United Kingdom House of Commons|House of Commons]] at the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]],<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=52903|page=7176|date=24 April 1992\n}}</ref> and made several speeches outlining his strong support for the [[European Union]]. Although sidelined during the brief period when [[John Smith (Labour Party leader)|John Smith]] led the party, Mandelson was by now close to two [[Shadow Cabinet]] members \u2013 [[Gordon Brown]] and [[Tony Blair]] \u2013 each regarded as potential future [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|leaders of the party]].\n\nFollowing Smith's sudden death on 12 May 1994, Mandelson chose to back Blair for the leadership, believing him to be a superior communicator to Brown<ref name=\"Blair story\">{{cite news|title=The Tony Blair Story|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6506365.stm|work=BBC News|date=10 May 2007|accessdate=23 September 2008}}</ref> and played a leading role in the leadership campaign. This created antagonism between Mandelson and Brown, though they were considered allies in the Labour Party.<ref name=\"it's love\">{{cite news|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/uk-politics/2009/06/mandelson-brown-blair-prime |title=Brown and Mandelson: It's Love|newspaper=New Statesman|accessdate=13 April 2010}}</ref> In 1994 [[Kate Garvey]] suggested that Mandelson (who was at the time being derided by the trade unions and other Labour factions), should adopt a \"[[nom de guerre]]\" throughout Blair's leadership bid, so that he might conceal his considerable role within the campaign team. Mandelson agreed to be called \"Bobby\" for the duration and was thanked by Blair using this name in his victory speech.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=_v8LAQAAMAAJ&q=%22kate+garvey%22+mandelson+bobby&dq=%22kate+garvey%22+mandelson+bobby|authorlink=Cherie Blair |page=173 |title=Speaking for myself: The autobiography |isbn=9781408700983 |last1=Blair |first1=Cherie |year=2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nextleft.org/2010/08/peter-breaks-cover-again-as-blairite.html |title=Peter breaks cover (again) as the Blairite battalions come out }}</ref>\n\nAfter becoming a close ally and trusted adviser to [[Tony Blair]], Mandelson was Labour's election campaign director for the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]], which Labour won decisively.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/commentators/peter-mandelson-labours-election-campaign-needs--to-express-its-vision-and-beliefs-684602.html|title=Peter Mandelson: Labour's election campaign needs to express its vision and beliefs|newspaper=The Independent|location=UK|accessdate=12 August 2009|date=14 May 2001 }}</ref>\n\n=== Minister without Portfolio ===\nHe was appointed as a [[Minister without Portfolio]] in the [[Cabinet Office]], where his job was to co-ordinate within government. A few months later, he also acquired responsibility for the [[Millennium Dome]], after Blair decided to go ahead with the project despite the opposition of most of the cabinet (including the [[Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport]] who had been running it). [[Jennifer Page (Millenium Dome)|Jennie Page]], the Dome project's chief executive, was abruptly sacked after a farcical opening night.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/topics/people/Lord_Mandelson|title=Peter Mandelson|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-09-03}}</ref> She gave evidence to a House of Commons Select Committee for Culture and Heritage in June 2000. In what was seen as a reference to the close interest in the Dome from Mandelson, known at the time as so-called \"Dome Secretary\" and his successor [[Lord Falconer of Thoroton]], Page told the committee: \"I made several attempts to persuade ministers that standing back from the Dome would be good for them as well as good for the Dome\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Page told ministers to stay away from Dome', ''The Independent''|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/this-britain/page-told-ministers-to-stay-away-from-dome-715271.html|accessdate=31 July 2008|location=London|first=Severin|last=Carrell|date=16 June 2000}}</ref>\n\nIn July 1998 he was appointed to the Cabinet as [[Secretary of State for Trade and Industry]]; he launched the [[Y2K|Millennium Bug And Electronic Commerce Bill]] and a Competitiveness [[White Paper]], which he described, as 'bold, far reaching and absolutely necessary'. He also appointed a \"[[Internet|Net]] Tsar\" to lead the UK in what he termed the \"new industrial revolution\". In 1998 he was appointed a [[Privy Counsellor]].\n\nMandelson bought a home in [[Notting Hill]] in 1996 partly with an interest-free loan of \u00a3373,000 from [[Geoffrey Robinson]], a cabinet colleague and millionaire whose business dealings were subject to an inquiry by Mandelson's department.<ref name=\"resignation1\">{{cite news |title=Double resignation rocks government |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/241464.stm |work=BBC News |date=23 December 1998 |accessdate=13 February 2007}}</ref> Mandelson contended that he had deliberately not taken part in any decisions relating to Robinson. However, he had not declared the loan in the [[Register of Members' Interests]] and resigned in December 1998.<ref name=\"resignation1\" /> Mandelson had also not declared the loan to his building society (the [[Britannia Building Society|Britannia]]) although they decided not to take any action, with the CEO stating \"I am satisfied that the information given to us at the time of the mortgage application was accurate.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Mandelson gets mortgage all-clear |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/251125.stm|work=BBC News|date=8 January 1999|accessdate=13 February 2007}}</ref> Mandelson initially thought he could weather the press storm, but had to resign when it became clear that the Prime Minister thought nothing else would clear the air.<ref>{{cite news|authorlink=Andrew Rawnsley|last=Rawnsley|first=Andrew |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=17 September 2000|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2000/sep/17/mandelson.labour2|title=The house comes tumbling down |location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2000 it was reported that Robinson had \"accused Peter Mandelson of lying to the Commons about the home loan affair that cost both of them their government jobs.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Brogan|first=Benedict |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1370559/Mandelson-lied-over-home-loan.html |title=Mandelson 'lied over home loan' |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=16 October 2000|accessdate=13 April 2010 |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/mandelson-lied-over-loan-634660.html|title=Mandelson 'lied' over loan|newspaper=The Independent|location=London|date=16 October 2000}}</ref>\n\n=== Secretary of State for Northern Ireland ===\nHe was out of the Cabinet for ten months. In October 1999 he was appointed [[Secretary of State for Northern Ireland]], replacing [[Mo Mowlam]]. In his very first speech in the post he mistakenly referred to himself as the \"Secretary of State for Ireland.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Mandelson passes first Commons test|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/480695.stm|work=BBC News|date=20 October 1999|accessdate=13 February 2007}}</ref> During his tenure he oversaw the creation of the [[Northern Ireland Assembly|devolved legislative assembly]] and [[Northern Ireland Executive|power-sharing executive]] and reform of the [[Police Service of Northern Ireland|police service]].\n\nOn 24 January 2001 Mandelson resigned from the [[UK Government|Government]] for a second time, following accusations of using his position to influence a passport application.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/1134819.stm |title=Mandelson resigns over Hinduja affair |work=BBC News|date= 24 January 2001|accessdate=3 October 2008}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=56106|page=1223|date=31 January 2001}}</ref> He had contacted [[Home Office]] Minister [[Mike O'Brien (UK politician)|Mike O'Brien]] on behalf of [[Hindujas|Srichand Hinduja]], an Indian businessman who was seeking British citizenship and whose family firm was to become the main sponsor of the \"Faith Zone\" in the [[Millennium Dome]]. At the time Hinduja and his brothers were under investigation by the Indian government for alleged involvement in the [[Bofors scandal]]. Mandelson insisted he had done nothing wrong and was exonerated by an independent inquiry by Sir Anthony Hammond, which concluded that neither Mandelson nor anyone else had acted improperly. The front-page headline in ''[[The Independent]]'' read in part \"Passport to Oblivion\".<ref>Andrew Grice, \"The Mandelson Resignation: Passport to Oblivion\", ''The Independent'', 25 January 2001</ref>\n\nAt the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]] Mandelson was challenged by [[Arthur Scargill]] of the [[Socialist Labour Party (UK)|Socialist Labour Party]] and by John Booth, a former Labour Party press officer standing as \"Genuine Labour\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/1314307.stm|title=Mandelson faces new challenger|date=5 May 2001|work=BBC News |accessdate=5 April 2009}}</ref> but Mandelson was re-elected with a large majority.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://politics.guardian.co.uk/hoc/constituency/0,,-1005,00.html |title=Hartlepool |last=Ask Aristotle |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=5 April 2009 |location=London |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090312051426/http://politics.guardian.co.uk/hoc/constituency/0%2C%2C-1005%2C00.html |archivedate=12 March 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> This prompted him to make an exuberant acceptance speech, which was televised live, in which he declared that \"I'm a fighter, not a quitter\"<ref name=\"bbc-profile\" /> and referred to his \"inner steel\".\n\n=== Stepping down as MP ===\nDespite Labour success in the June 2001 general election, a third Cabinet appointment did not materialise and he indicated his interest in becoming the United Kingdom's [[European Commissioner]] when the new [[European Commission|Commission]] was established in 2004. Both of Britain's Commissioners, [[Neil Kinnock]] and [[Chris Patten]], were due to stand down. Appointment as a European Commissioner would require his resignation from Parliament precipitating a [[by-election]] in his Hartlepool constituency. His appointment was announced in the summer and on 8 September 2004 Mandelson resigned his seat by submitting his name as [[Steward of the Manor of Northstead]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.scotsman.com/petermandelson/Mandelson-appointed-to-lead-EU.2554339.jp|title=Mandelson appointed to lead EU trade|newspaper=The Scotsman|location=UK|date=17 August 2004|accessdate=28 November 2009|first=James|last=Kirkup}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=57414 |page=11832|date=20 September 2004\n}}</ref> Labour won the subsequent [[2004 Hartlepool by-election|Hartlepool by-election]] with a much-reduced majority of 2,033 votes (equating to 40.7% of the vote).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2004/oct/01/uk.byelections|title=Tories pushed into fourth place as Labour holds on to Hartlepool|newspaper=The Guardian |location=UK |date=1 October 2004|accessdate=28 November 2009|first=Patrick|last=Wintour}}</ref> He was succeeded as MP for Hartlepool by [[Iain Wright]].\n\n=== European Commissioner ===\nOn 22 November 2004 Mandelson became Britain's European Commissioner, taking the [[European Commissioner for Trade|trade portfolio]].\n\nIn October 2008 he left his post as Trade Commissioner to return to UK politics. As a former EU Commissioner, Lord Mandelson is entitled to a \u00a331,000 pension when he reaches the age of 65 years. This however is contingent on a \"duty of loyalty to the Communities\", which applies also after his term in office.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/4996440/Lord-Mandelson-must-remain-loyal-to-EU-to-guarantee-pension.html|title=Lord Mandelson must remain loyal to EU to guarantee pension|last=Editor|first=Christopher Hope, Whitehall|date=2009-03-16|access-date=2018-09-03|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> The [[Taxpayers' Alliance]], which uncovered the threat to his pension, demanded that he should declare the conflict of interest and either relinquish his EU pay cheques or resign as a [[minister (diplomacy)|minister]]. \"When one considers that his new ministerial post deals specifically with business, enterprise and regulatory reform \u2013 all areas that are intimately involved with EU legislation, regulation and policy \u2013\" the group said, \"the conflict of interest is even more stark.\" Mandelson did not agree that he had a conflict of interests. \"He has always had a clear view of British interests and how they are secured by our EU membership,\" a spokesperson said.<ref>Christopher Hope: [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/labour/4996440/Lord-Mandelson-must-remain-loyal-to-EU-to-guarantee-pension.html Lord Mandelson must remain loyal to EU to guarantee pension] ''The Daily Telegraph'', 16 March 2009.</ref>\n\n===Peerage and return to Cabinet===\n[[File:Gordon Brown and Peter Mandelson.jpg|right|thumb|Mandelson (left) with [[Gordon Brown]] at the Progressive Governance Conference, February 2010.]]\nOn 3 October 2008, as part of [[Gordon Brown]]'s Cabinet reshuffle, it was announced amid some controversy<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/news/legal-and-constitutional/mandelson-becomes-peer-amid-controversy-$1244576.htm |title=Mandelson becomes peer amid controversy |publisher=Politics|accessdate=13 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Nicholas Watt|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/oct/13/mandelson-lords |title=Peter Mandelson goes to Lords amid new controversy|newspaper=The Guardian|location=UK|date=13 October 2008|accessdate=13 April 2010}}</ref> that Mandelson would return to [[Her Majesty's Government|Government]] in the re-designated post of [[Secretary of State for Business, Enterprise and Regulatory Reform|Business Secretary]] and would be raised to the [[life peer|peerage]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/3127802/Peter-Mandelson-profile-The-Prince-of-Darkness-returns.html|title=Peter Mandelson profile: The Prince of Darkness returns|last=Swaine|first=Jon|date=2008-10-03|access-date=2019-02-26|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> thus becoming a [[member of the House of Lords]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7650013.stm|title= Mandelson to return to government|work=BBC News|accessdate=3 October 2008 | date=3 October 2008}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=58848 |page=15551|date=10 October 2008 }}</ref> On 13 October 2008 he was created '''Baron Mandelson''', of [[Foy, Herefordshire|Foy]] in the County of [[Herefordshire]] and of [[Hartlepool]] in the County of [[County Durham|Durham]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=58855 |page=15991 |date=17 October 2008}}</ref> and was [[Introduction (House of Lords)|introduced]] in the [[House of Lords]] the same day.<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200708/minutes/081014/ldordpap.htm#minproc House of Lords Minute of Proceedings of Monday 13 October 2008].</ref>\n\nFollowing his return to office, Mandelson supported [[Expansion of London Heathrow Airport|the planned Heathrow expansion]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23601732-mandelson-throws-his-weight-behind-third-heathrow-runway.do|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130505090244/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23601732-mandelson-throws-his-weight-behind-third-heathrow-runway.do|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 May 2013|title=Mandelson throws his weight behind third Heathrow runway|newspaper=London Evening Standard|date=15 December 2008|accessdate=27 November 2009}}</ref> On 6 March 2009, environmental protester [[Leila Deen]] of anti-aviation group [[Plane Stupid]] approached him outside a summit on the government's low carbon industrial strategy and threw a cup of green custard in his face in protest over his support for a third runway at Heathrow Airport. The protester was cautioned on 9 April for causing \"harassment, alarm or distress\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/7991907.stm |title=Mandelson custard woman cautioned|date=9 April 2009 |work=BBC News|accessdate=15 April 2009}}</ref><ref>Hines, Nico: [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article5856186.ece Protester throws green custard in the face of Lord Mandelson and walks away] ''The Times'', 6 March 2009</ref>\n\nIn a Cabinet reshuffle on 5 June 2009 Mandelson was granted the honorific title of [[First Secretary of State]] and appointed [[Lord President of the Council]];<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/jun/05/cabinet-reshuffle-gordon-brown-ed-balls|title=Weakened Gordon Brown unable to shift cabinet's bigger beasts|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=5 June 2008|location=London|first=Patrick|last=Wintour}}</ref> it was also announced that the [[Department for Innovation, Universities and Skills]] would be merged into his, giving him the new title of [[Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills]] and that he would continue as [[President of the Board of Trade]].<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\" /><ref>[http://number10.gov.uk/ Full list of Cabinet members], Prime Minister's Office, 5 June 2009</ref>\n\nMandelson was a member of 35 of the 43 Cabinet committees and subcommittees.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/5882622/Lord-Mandelsons-empire-35-Cabinet-committee-posts.html| newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|title=Lord Mandelson's empire: 35 Cabinet committee posts|first=Murray|last=Wardrop | date=22 July 2009|accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2009 Mandelson was widely reported to have ordered \"technical measures\" such as internet disconnection to be included in the draft of the [[Digital Economy Act 2010]] after a \"big lobbying operation\", even though the [[Digital Britain]] report had rejected this type of punishment.<ref name=\"timesAug2009\">{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article6809329.ece|first=Sam|last=Coates|title=Families could lose broadband access as Mandelson takes on web pirates|newspaper=Times|date=26 August 2009|accessdate=21 April 2011|location=London}}</ref> ''[[The Independent]]'' reported that according to their Whitehall sources, Mandelson was persuaded that tough laws were needed to reduce online copyright infringement following an intensive lobbying campaign by influential people in the music and film industry.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/the-net-closes-in-on-internet-piracy-1772820.html|title=The Net closes in on internet piracy|newspaper=The Independent|date=16 August 2009|accessdate=25 November 2009|location=London}}</ref> The paper also reported that this included a meeting with [[DreamWorks Pictures|DreamWorks]] co-founder [[David Geffen]] at the [[Rothschild]] family villa on the Greek island of Corfu. Mandelson's spokesperson claimed that there had been no discussion of internet piracy during the Corfu dinner and suggested that the decision to reverse Lord Carter's findings had been taken in late July before the trip. ''[[The Times]]'' reported after the Corfu meeting that an unnamed Whitehall source had confirmed that before this trip, Mandelson had shown little personal interest in the Digital Britain agenda, which has been ongoing for several years. According to the source of ''The Times'', Mandelson returned from holiday and effectively issued an edict that the regulation needed to be tougher.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://technology.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/tech_and_web/the_web/article6797844.ece|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110403114449/http://technology.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/tech_and_web/the_web/article6797844.ece|archivedate=3 April 2011|title=Mandelson targets web pirates after dinner with mogul|newspaper=The Times|date=16 August 2009|accessdate=6 January 2009|location=London|first=Jonathan|last=Oliver}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2011 a [[Freedom of information in the United Kingdom|Freedom of Information]] (FOI) request showed that Mandelson had decided to approve the inclusion of technical measures, such as the disconnection of internet access, at least two months before public consultation had finished and that he had shown little interest in the consultation. Letters from Mandelson's office document talks with [[Lucian Grainge]], CEO of [[Universal Music Group]] on 2 June 2009 and that on the following day Mandelson advised [[Stephen Carter, Baron Carter of Barnes|Lord Carter]] about the \"possibility of [the Secretary of State] having a power to direct Ofcom to go directly to introduce technical measures\". Mandelson made the formal announcement that technical measures, including disconnection, were to be included in the Digital Economy Bill two months later on 7 August 2009.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wilson|first=Dean| title=Documents show the Digital Economy Act was a done deal all along| publisher=The Inquirer| date=1 August 2011|url= http://www.theinquirer.net/inquirer/news/2098344/documents-digital-economy-act-deal| accessdate=14 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nAn opinion poll conducted by the centre-left think tank [[Compass (think tank)|Compass]] found in March 2009 that Mandelson was less disliked by party members than Deputy Leader [[Harriet Harman]]. This was felt to be unusual as Mandelson \"historically has been unpopular among Labour members\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/labour/4953559/Harriet-Harman-less-popular-than-Peter-Mandelson-among-Labour-members.html|title= Harriet Harman less popular than Peter Mandelson among Labour members |work=Telegraph webside|accessdate=8 March 2009 | location=London | first=Patrick | last=Hennessy | date=7 March 2009}}</ref> [[Tony Blair]]'s assertion in 1996 that \"my project will be complete when the Labour Party learns to love Peter Mandelson\"<ref>cited in ''The Daily Telegraph'', 2 March 1996, [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/3750847.stm \"Blair: In his own words\"], BBC News Channel, 11 May 2007</ref> was seen as prophetic in late September 2009 when Mandelson was enthusiastically received at the [[Labour Party (UK) Conference|party conference]] in Brighton.<ref>Ben Wright [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8279705.stm \"Labour learns to love Mandelson\"], BBC ''News at Ten'', 28 September 2009</ref>\n\n== Post-Cabinet career ==\nAfter the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] lost the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], Mandelson's memoirs, ''[[The Third Man: Life at the Heart of New Labour]]'', were published in July 2010, two months after leaving office.<ref>Andrew Rawnsley [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2010/jul/18/peter-mandelson-third-man-memoirs \"''The Third Man'' by Peter Mandelson\"], ''The Observer'', 18 July 2010</ref><ref>Matthew d'Ancona [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/7906908/The-Third-Man-by-Peter-Mandelson-review.html \"''The Third Man'' by Peter Mandelson: review\"], ''The Daily Telegraph'', 28 July 2010</ref> The memoirs were subsequently criticised by Labour leadership contenders [[Ed Miliband|Ed]] and [[David Miliband]] and [[Andy Burnham]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-10671510 |work=BBC News|title=Mandelson memoirs condemned by Labour leadership rivals |date=17 July 2010}}</ref> During this time he was appointed President of the international think tank [[Policy Network]].\n\nIn November 2010, Mandelson and [[Benjamin Wegg-Prosser]] founded [[Global Counsel]], a consultancy firm based in London, with the financial support of WPP, the advertising giant.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/8169875/Lord-Mandelson-to-head-classy-consultancy-firm.html |location=London |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |first=Nick |last=Collins |title=Lord Mandelson to head 'classy' consultancy firm |date=30 November 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"ft-20130531\">{{cite news |url=http://blogs.ft.com/westminster/2013/05/mandelson-looks-east-for-russian-directorship/ |title=Mandelson looks east for Russian directorship |author=Jim Pickard |newspaper=Financial Times |date=31 May 2013 |accessdate=9 August 2013}}</ref> The firm provides advice for [[Strategic management|corporate strategists and senior management]] worldwide. Mandelson has been criticised for so far not disclosing his clients.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/Politics/article1534435.ece?CMP=OTH-gnws-standard-2015_03_22|title=Mandelson faces having to name business clients|date=22 March 2015|newspaper=The Sunday Times|accessdate=30 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, 2008, 2009, 2011, 2012, 2013 and 2014 Mandelson was an invited guest of the [[Bilderberg Group]] and attended the annual conferences.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199900/cmregmem/memi19.htm|title=British House of Commons \u2013 Register of Journalists' Interests|publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom|author=House of Commons|accessdate=13 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/blog/2009/may/19/bilderberg-skelton-greece|title=Our man at Bilderberg|last=Skelton|first=Charlie|date=19 May 2009|work=The Guardian|location=UK|quote=Mandelson's office has confirmed his attendance at this year's meeting: \"Yes, Lord Mandelson attended Bilberberg. He found it a valuable conference.\"|accessdate=20 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2011, it was announced that Mandelson would serve as a senior adviser to the advisory investment banking firm, [[Lazard]].<ref>{{cite news |publisher=Lazard, Ltd. |title=Press Release: Lord Mandelson to Serve as a Senior Adviser to Lazard |url=http://www.lazard.com/PDF/Lazard%20-%20Mandelson%201-21-2011.pdf |accessdate=11 March 2011 |date=21 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713192049/http://www.lazard.com/PDF/Lazard%20-%20Mandelson%201-21-2011.pdf |archivedate=13 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"telegraph-20110821\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/8714791/Mandelson-poised-to-buy-8m-home.html|title=Mandelson poised to buy \u00a38m home|date=21 August 2011|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|author=Holly Watt|accessdate=20 January 2015}}</ref> In 2013, he also joined the Board of Trustees of [[Deutsche Bank]]'s Alfred Herrhausen Gesellschaft.<ref>[https://www.alfred-herrhausen-gesellschaft.de/en/kuratorium.htm Board of Trustees] Alfred Herrhausen Gesellschaft of [[Deutsche Bank]].</ref> In May 2011 it was revealed that there was speculation that Mandelson had been approached by [[China]] to be a candidate for the leadership of the [[International Monetary Fund]], even though Mandelson had not been a [[finance minister]] or headed a [[central bank]]. However, it was then speculated that Mandelson would stand to succeed [[Pascal Lamy]] as Director-General of the [[World Trade Organization]], backed by [[David Cameron]].\n\nIn May 2012, Mandelson confirmed that he was advising [[Asia Pulp & Paper]] (APP) in selling timber products to Europe. In 2012 APP was accused of [[illegal logging]] in [[Indonesia]] and damaging the habitats of rare animals such as the [[Sumatran tiger]]. At least 67 companies worldwide, such as [[Tesco]] and [[Kraft Foods]] since 2004 and [[Danone]] since 2012 have boycotted APP.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/may/10/mandelson-advises-company-rainforest Lord Mandelson confirms he is advising company accused of illegal logging] Peer's consultancy works for paper and pulp multinational alleged to have chopped down protected trees Guardian 10 May 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.greenpeace.org/international/en/news/Blogs/makingwaves/yoghurt-for-forests-danone-drops-asia-pulp-an/blog/39818/ Yoghurt for forests! Danone drops Asia Pulp and Paper, plans zero deforestation policy] [[Greenpeace]] 2 April 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.greenpeace.org/international/Global/international/publications/forests/2012/Indonesia/Greenpeace_TRPT_report.docx The Ramin Paper Trail Asia Pulp & Paper Under Investigation \u2013 Part 2] [http://www.greenpeace.org/international/en/publications/Campaign-reports/Forests-Reports/The-Ramin-Paper-Trail in short] [[Greenpeace]] 1 March 2012</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Mandelson was appointed to the revived post of [[High Steward of Hull]], a ceremonial position held by his grandfather [[Herbert Morrison]] in 1956\u201365 and defunct [[Local Government Act 1972|since 1974]].<ref name=\"bbc21290844\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-humber-21290844|title=East Yorkshire city brings back ancient roles|work=BBC News|accessdate=19 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Labour leadership of Jeremy Corbyn===\nAfter the [[2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2015 Labour leadership election]] resulted in [[Jeremy Corbyn]] becoming the [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|party leader]], Mandelson stated that he believed that Labour was now unelectable, but advised party members unhappy with the situation to wait for Corbyn to demonstrate this before working to replace him.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34355545 |title=Lord Mandelson: Don't rush to oust Jeremy Corbyn |work=BBC News |date=25 September 2015|accessdate=27 July 2016}}</ref> He wished for an early general election to force Corbyn out.<ref name=guardian-20160927>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/sep/27/peter-mandelson-i-am-praying-for-early-election |title=Peter Mandelson 'praying' for early election to end 'awful' Labour saga |last=Weaver |first=Matthew |newspaper=The Guardian |date=27 September 2016 |accessdate=16 June 2017}}</ref> In February 2017, he said Corbyn had \"no idea in the 21st century how to conduct himself as a leader of a party putting itself forward in a democratic election\" and \"I work every single day to bring forward the end of [Corbyn's] tenure in office\".<ref name=telegraph-20170221>{{cite news|last=Hughes|first=Laura|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/02/21/lord-mandelson-working-every-single-day-bring-end-jeremy-corbyns/ |title=Lord Mandelson: I am working 'every single day' to bring an end to Jeremy Corbyn's leadership |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=21 February 2017 |accessdate=21 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter the results of the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]] became known, Mandelson conceded that Corbyn's election campaign was \"very sure footed\" and the result, in which Labour gained seats and denied the Conservatives a majority, unexpected.<ref>{{cite news|last=Merrick|first=Rob|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/r-a7782766.html|title=Jeremy Corbyn strengthens his grip on the Labour party as harshest critics change their tune|work=The Independent|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=16 June 2017}}</ref> \"I was wrong\" about Corbyn, he told BBC News. \"I am very surprised, an earthquake has happened in British politics and I did not foresee it\", although he doubted Corbyn's ability to gain a Commons majority.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mairs|first=Nicholas|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/jeremy-corbyn/news/86571/i-was-clearly-wrong-jeremy-corbyns|title='I was clearly wrong' - Jeremy Corbyn's Labour critics congratulate the leader|work=Politics Home|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=16 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Remain Campaign ==\nDuring the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 EU referendum]], Mandelson sat on the board on [[Britain Stronger in Europe|Britain Stronger IN Europe]], the official \"Remain\" campaign. The campaign was unsuccessful.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/98619e5c-3f70-11e6-8716-a4a71e8140b0|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-02-26}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the referendum, Mandelson was an outspoken supporter of a [[People's Vote]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/final-say-peter-mandelson-brexit-referendum-peoples-vote-theresa-may-tory-cornservatives-a8469666.html|title=Fresh Brexit referendum could empower Theresa May to 'stand up against Brextremists' blackmail', says Peter Mandelson|date=2018-07-30|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-02-26}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\nDuring the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal|2009 expenses scandal]] ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' raised questions about the timing of Mandelson's second home allowance claim, dating from 2004, saying, \"Lord Mandelson billed the taxpayer for almost \u00a33,000 of work on his constituency home in Hartlepool less than a week after announcing his decision to stand down as an MP.\" Mandelson said in a statement, \"The work done was necessary maintenance. All claims made were reasonable and submitted consistent with parliamentary rules.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5293035/MPs-expenses-Questions-over-timing-of-Peter-Mandelsons-house-claim.html|title=MPs expenses: Questions over timing of Peter Mandelson's house claim|last=Prince|first=Rosa|date=8 May 2009|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|accessdate=18 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 April 2005 ''[[The Times]]'' revealed that Mandelson had spent the previous New Year's Eve on the yacht of [[Paul Allen]], the co-founder of [[Microsoft]], which was at the centre of a major EU investigation and although it did not allege impropriety, it did state that Mandelson's visit was inappropriate for a serving European Commissioner.<ref>Anthony Browne, Daniel McGrory and Lewis Smith [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/europe/article384041.ece \"Mandelson, the computer king and a party on a luxury yacht\",] ''The Times'', 22 April 2009</ref>\n\nDuring the summer of 2008 Mandelson had a widely publicised disagreement with [[Nicolas Sarkozy]], [[President of France]].<ref name=\"bbc-profile\" /> Sarkozy accused him of trying to sell out European farmers and appeared to blame his handling of the Doha round of trade talks for the \"no\" vote in the [[Twenty-eighth Amendment of the Constitution Bill, 2008 (Ireland)|Irish referendum]] on the [[Treaty of Lisbon]]. Mandelson said his position at world trade talks had been undermined and told the [[BBC]] he did not start the row, saying, \"I stood up for myself, I'm not to be bullied.\" He said he believed the row was over but renewed his warnings on [[protectionism]].<ref name=\"bbc-profile\" />\n\nIn 2008 Mandelson was hospitalised, suffering from a kidney stone. At this time, [[melamine]] added to [[2008 Chinese milk scandal|milk in China]] had caused kidney stones and other ailments in thousands of Chinese children, killing at least six. Ironically, during the previous week Mandelson had drunk a glass of Chinese yoghurt in front of reporters in order to show his confidence in Chinese dairy products, although his own kidney stones were unrelated.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/labour/3144271/Peter-Mandelson-to-have-kidney-stone-removed.html|title=Peter Mandelson to have kidney stone removed|date=6 October 2008|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|location=UK|author=Jon Swaine|accessdate=7 September 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/archive/news/mandelson-ill-after-yoghurt-in-china/story-e6frg6t6-1111117689177?nk=8ce946fc6104191a0524d770da72f62c|title=British politician Peter Mandelson ill after yoghurt in China|date=8 October 2008|work=The Australian|author=Rowan Callick|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2008 Mandelson was reported to have maintained private contacts over several years with Russian oligarch [[Oleg Deripaska]], most recently on holiday in August 2008 on Deripaska's yacht at Taverna Agni on the Greek island of [[Corfu]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article4982163.ece|title=Lord Mandelson and Oleg Deripaska dined together 'a year before they met'|last=Robertson|first=David|date=21 October 2008|newspaper=The Times|location=UK|accessdate=23 October 2008}}</ref> News of the contacts sparked criticism because, as European Union Trade Commissioner, Mandelson had been responsible for two decisions to cut aluminium tariffs that had benefited Deripaska's United Company [[RusAl]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.moscowtimes.ru/article/1010/42/371829.htm|title=UK. Conservatives Linked to Deripaska|date=22 October 2008|newspaper=[[The Moscow Times]]|accessdate=23 October 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081126051311/http://www.moscowtimes.ru/article/1010/42/371829.htm|archivedate=26 November 2008}}</ref> Mandelson denied that there had been a [[conflict of interest]] and insisted that he had never discussed aluminium tariffs with Deripaska.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article4932191.ece|title=Peter Mandelson dogged by his links to Russian oligarch|date=13 October 2008|newspaper=The Times|last2=Charter|first2=David|location=UK|accessdate=23 October 2008|first1=David|last1=Robertson}}</ref> On 26 October 2008 the [[Shadow Foreign Secretary]] [[William Hague]] claimed the \"whole country\" wanted \"transparency\" about Mandelson's previous meetings with Deripaska. In response, Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]] said Mandelson's dealings with Deripaska had been \"found to be above board\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7691678.stm|title=Tories seek Mandelson 'clarity'|date=26 October 2008|work=BBC News|accessdate=30 October 2008}}</ref> Mandelson said that meeting business figures from \"across the range\" in emerging economies was part of his brief as EU Trade Commissioner.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/oct/28/peter-mandelson-oleg-deripaska-corfu|title=Mandelson silent on Deripaska|last=Parfitt|first=Tom|date=28 October 2008|newspaper=The Guardian|location=UK|accessdate=30 October 2008}}</ref> On 29 October 2008, while Mandelson was on a ministerial visit to Moscow,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/oct/29/russia-mandelson|title=Mandelson hails thaw in relations with Moscow|last=Parfitt|first=Tom|date=29 October 2008|newspaper=The Guardian|location=UK|accessdate=30 October 2008}}</ref> it was alleged in the British press that [[Valery Pechyonkin|Valery Pechenkin]], the head of security at Deripaska's company Basic Element, had organised a swift entry visa for Mandelson when he turned up in [[Moscow]] to visit Deripaska in 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23579423-details/Veteran+KGB+spy+revealed+as+Deripaska%27s+right-hand+man/article.do|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081101053919/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23579423-details/Veteran+KGB+spy+revealed+as+Deripaska%27s+right-hand+man/article.do|url-status=dead|archive-date=1 November 2008|title=Veteran KGB spy revealed as Deripaska's right-hand man|date=29 October 2008|newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]]|accessdate=30 October 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2013, writing for the [[Progress (organisation)|Progress website]], Mandelson warned Labour it risked harming its election chances if [[affiliated trade unions]] continued to \"manipulate parliamentary selections\" as was alleged in the [[2013 Labour Party Falkirk candidate selection]] controversy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.progressonline.org.uk/2013/06/27/no-more-falkirks/|title=No more Falkirks|publisher=progressonline.org.uk|accessdate=19 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/jun/27/labour-mandelson-unions-unite-legal-falkirk | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Patrick | last=Wintour | title=Unite threatens Labour with legal action over Falkirk row | date=27 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2014 it was reported that Mandelson had strong ties to Russian conglomerate [[Sistema]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/10744744/Peter-Mandelson-refuses-to-defend-links-to-Russian-defence-firm.html|title=Peter Mandelson refuses to defend links to Russian defence firm|date=4 April 2014|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=19 August 2015|last1=Holehouse|first1=Matthew}}</ref>\n\n== Non-political commitments ==\nMandelson was until 8 October 2008 the President of [[Central School of Speech and Drama]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmregmem/memi19.htm|title=The House of Commons \u2013 Register of Members' Interests|publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom|author=House of Commons|accessdate=13 April 2010}}</ref> He was replaced in this un-remunerated post by playwright [[Harold Pinter]], who died two months later.\n\nIn 2011, Mandelson was guest of honour at Herbert Morrison Primary School in Vauxhall, South London. The school was hosting a special themed day in honour of Mandelson's grandfather, Herbert Morrison, after whom the school was named.\n\n==Personal life==\n\n=== Partner and sexuality ===\nMandelson is gay and he is said to be 'intensely private' about his personal life.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/the-truth-was-out-and-so-were-the-knives-1088357.html|title=The truth was 'out'. And so were the knives|date=1999-04-20|newspaper=The Independent|access-date=2017-02-21|language=en-GB}}</ref> During his time as a former government leader, the press \u2013 tabloid and broadsheet alike \u2013 often portrayed Mandelson as effeminate through \"the linguistic resources of camp\" (as evidenced through his common nickname, 'Mandy') and narcissistic \u2013 sometimes including coded references to homosexual acts in their descriptions of his actions.<ref>Morrish, L. (2002) '\"That's so typical of Peter \u2013 as soon as there's a cock-up he tries to sit on it\": British Broadsheet Press versus Peter Mandleson 1996\u2013 2001.' Paper given at the ''9th Annual American University Conference on Lavender Languages and Linguistics''.</ref>\n\nHe has lived with his life partner Reinaldo Avila da Silva, a [[Brazilians|Brazilian-British]] translator, since March 1998.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/4258915/Is-stricken-Mandy-likely-to-lose-Reinaldo-too.html|title=Is stricken Mandy likely to lose Reinaldo, too?|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=2017-02-21|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Attempted outings and harassment ===\nWhile his sexual orientation was known to friends, colleagues and constituents, in 1987 the ''[[News of the World]]'' ran an issue that attempted to out Mandelson as gay.<ref name=\":0\" /> Mandelson preferred to keep his personal life private and as such did not respond.<ref name=\"Tatchell-1998\">{{cite news|url=http://www.petertatchell.net/celebrities/petermandelson/|title=Why Mandy Won't Let Sexuality Queer the Pitch|date=31 January 1998|work=Punch|last1=Tatchell|first1=Peter|authorlink1=Peter Tatchell}}</ref> Mandelson was outed again by [[Matthew Parris]] in 1998 on the BBC programme ''[[Newsnight]]''.<ref name=\"BBC-2010\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-10973463|title=BBC to replay clip of Lord Mandelson being 'outed'|date=14 August 2010|work=BBC News}}</ref> This led to press harassment of his partner, with the ''[[Daily Express]]'' sending a reporter to take pictures of him while he was at his languages course.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nAn internal investigation later found that the photos had been obtained without Avila da Silva's consent and images of him attempting to cover his face had been secretly deleted. Mandelson phoned the BBC and the [[Press Complaints Commission]] following ''Newsnight''{{'s}} broadcast,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/mandelson-phoned-bbc-after-being-outed-1.212032|title=Mandelson phoned BBC after being 'outed'|date=7 November 1998|work=The Irish Times}}</ref> and an internal memo was later sent within the BBC, stating that \"Under no circumstances whatsoever should allegations about the private life of Peter Mandelson be repeated or referred to on any broadcast.\"<ref name=\"BBC-2010\" />\n\n==In the media==\n* [[BBC Four]]'s ''[[Storyville (TV series)|Storyville]]'' in 2010, ''Mandelson: The Real PM?'', directed by [[Hannah Mary Rothschild|Hannah Rothschild]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00w4k2d |title=Storyville, 2010\u20132011, Mandelson: The Real PM? |publisher=BBC Four |date=28 November 2010 |accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref> a [[fly on the wall]] documentary about Mandelson as Business Secretary in the run up to the 2010 general election.\n* Mandelson was portrayed by [[Mark Gatiss]] in the 2015 [[Channel 4]] drama ''[[Coalition (film)|Coalition]]''.\n* Mandelson was portrayed by [[Nigel Planer]] in the 2011 comedy drama ''[[The Hunt for Tony Blair]]''.\n* The ''[[Little Britain]]'' character [[List of Little Britain characters#Sebastian Love|Sebastian Love]] was based on Mandelson\n\n==Honours==\n* [[Image:Legion Honneur Officier ribbon.svg|45px]] Officer, [[Legion of Honour|L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\nHe was made an Officier of the [[Legion of Honour]] in February 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mandelson receives French Legion d'honneur|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-38845392|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=3 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* (with [[Roger Liddle]]) ''The Blair Revolution: Can New Labour Deliver?'' Faber, 1996 {{ISBN|978-0571178186}} ; ''The Blair Revolution Revisited'', (2nd ed), Politicos, 2002, {{ISBN|978-1842750391}}\n* (contributor) ''[[The City in Europe and the World]]'', European Research Forum at London Metropolitan University, 2006 {{ISBN|978-0954744816}}\n* ''The Third Man: Life at the Heart of New Labour'' Harper Press, 2010 {{ISBN|978-0007395286}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Jones, Nicholas (2000): ''Sultans of Spin: The Media and the New Labour Government'' Orion Books, {{ISBN|0-7528-2769-3}}\n* [[Donald Macintyre (journalist)|Macintyre, Donald]] (1999): ''Mandelson: The Biography'' Harper Collins, {{ISBN|0-00-255943-9}}\n* [[Andrew Rawnsley|Rawnsley, Andrew]] (2001): ''Servants of the People: The Inside Story of New Labour'' Penguin Books, {{ISBN|0-14-027850-8}}\n* Routledge, Paul (1999): ''Mandy: The Unauthorised Biography of Peter Mandelson'' Simon & Schuster, {{ISBN|0-684-85175-X}}\n* [[Anthony Seldon|Seldon, Anthony]] (2005): ''Blair'' The Free Press, {{ISBN|0-7432-3212-7}}\n\n===Works===\n* Mandelson, Peter (1997): ''[http://digital.library.lse.ac.uk/objects/lse:boc326get Labour's next steps]'' Fabian Society\n* Mandelson, Peter (2002): ''The Blair Revolution Revisited'' Politico's, {{ISBN|1-84275-039-9}}\n* {{cite book|last=Mandelson|first=Peter|title=The Third Man: Life at the Heart of New Labour|year=2010|publisher=HarperPress|isbn=978-0007395286}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Peter Mandelson}}\n* [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/peer/10412/lord_mandelson Lord Mandelson, former MP - They Work For You] \n* [https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-mandelson/500 Peter Mandelson profile at UK Parliament]\n* [https://www.ft.com/topics/people/Lord_Mandelson Peter Mandelson | Financial Times]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170914202340/http://www.policy-network.net/ Policy Network]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/7650195.stm Profile: Peter Mandelson