{"title_page": "Coronado High School (Lubbock, Texas)", "text_new": "{{Infobox school\n  | name = Coronado High School\n  | motto = It's a great day to be a Mustang!\n  | image = Coronado High School, Lubbock, TX IMG_0233.JPG\n  | image_size =\n  | caption = Coronado High School at the intersection of Vicksburg Avenue and 34th Street in Lubbock\n  | established = 1965\n  | type = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]]\n  | principal = Julia Stephen\n  | enrollment = 2,010 (2016-17)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=4828500&ID=482850010889|title=CORONADO H S|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref>\n  | free_label = Colors <br /> Mascot\n  | free_text = Scarlet and Gold <br /> Mustang\n  | free_label2 = Motto\n  | free_text2 = College Ready, Career Ready and Life Ready\n  | location = 4910 29th Dr.<br/>[[Lubbock, Texas]] 79410\n  | coordinates = {{Coord|33.5646|-101.91439|type:edu_region:US-TX|display=inline,title}}\n  | website = {{URL|chs.lubbockisd.org}}\n}}\n'''Coronado High School''' is the second newest high school in the [[Lubbock Independent School District]]. Coronado, named for the Spanish conquistador and explorer [[Francisco V\u00e1squez de Coronado]], opened its doors in 1965 as the fourth high school in Lubbock, joining the list of Lubbock High, Monterey High and Dunbar High.  Estacado was built two years after Coronado opened, in 1967.  The mascot of the school is the Mustang and the school colors are Scarlet and Old Gold. Like the other high schools in Lubbock ISD, Coronado discontinued its block scheduling in the 2012\u201313 academic calendar. and went to an every class everyday schedule. The school serves the southwestern part of [[Lubbock, Texas]].  The Coronado male sports teams are known as the \"Mustangs\" with the female teams referred to as the \"Lady Mustangs\".\n\n==Notable alumni==\n*[[Jarrett Culver]], NBA shooting guard for the Minnesota Timberwolves. Played college basketball for the [[Texas Tech Red Raiders basketball|Texas Tech Red Raiders]].\n*[[Justin Duchscherer]], MLB relief pitcher with the [[Oakland Athletics]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Justin Duchscherer|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/d/duchsju01.shtml|publisher=BASEBALL REFERENCE. COM|accessdate=19 November 2013}}</ref> \n*[[Sonny Dykes]], head football coach at [[California Golden Bears]] \n*[[Landon Johnson]], NFL linebacker with the [[Carolina Panthers]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Landon Johnson|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JohnLa20.htm|publisher=pro-football-reference.com|accessdate=19 November 2013}}</ref> \n*[[Mark Lanier]], attorney and trial lawyer<ref>{{cite web|title=Mark Lanier|url=http://search.lubbockonline.com/fast-elements.php?type=standard&profile=lubbock&querystring=%22MARK%20LANIER%22|publisher=Lubbock Avalanche-Journal|accessdate=19 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120122031712/http://search.lubbockonline.com/fast-elements.php?type=standard&profile=lubbock&querystring=%22MARK%20LANIER%22|archive-date=22 January 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n*[[Matt Martin (baseball)|Matt Martin]], baseball coach with the Detroit Tigers<ref>[http://eedition.lubbockonline.com/sports/2016-05-15/lubbock-native-martin-witnesses-history-scherzer-strikes-out-20]</ref>\n*[[William C. McCool|Willie McCool]], one of the astronauts killed when the [[Space Shuttle Columbia|Columbia]] [[Space Shuttle Columbia disaster|disintegrated]] over [[Texas]]<ref>{{cite web|title=William C. McCool|url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/mccool.html|publisher=jsc.nasa.gov|accessdate=19 November 2013}}</ref> \n*[[Richie McDonald]], lead singer of the band [[Lonestar]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Richie McDonald|url=http://lubbockonline.com/entertainment/2011-07-16/mcdonald-looking-forward-30th-coronado-high-school-reunion#.UorEmMSTi3M|publisher=Lubbock Avalanche-Journal|accessdate=19 November 2013}}</ref